define({'abandon':{d:'to cease producing oil and gas from a well when it becomes unprofitable. a wildcat well may be abandoned after it has proven non-productive. Several steps are involved in abandoning a well: part of the casing may be removed and salvaged; one or more cement plugs placed in the borehole to prevent migration of fluids between the different formations penetrated by the borehole. In many countries it is necessary to secure permission form official agencies before a well may be abandoned.',l:''},'abnormal pressure':{d:'pressure exceeding or falling below the normal pressure to be expected at a given depth. Normal pressure increases approximately 0.465 psi per foot of depth (10.5 kPa per metre of depth). Thus, normal pressure at 10,000 feet is 4,650 psi.; abnormal pressure at this depth would be higher or lower than 4,650 psi. See pressure gradient.',l:''},'absolute permeability':{d:'a measure of the ability of a single fluid (such as water, gas, or oil) to flow through a rock formation when the formation is totally filled (saturated) with the single fluid. The permeability measure of the same rock filled with two or more fluids. Compare effective permeability.',l:''},'absolute porosity':{d:'percentage of the total bulk volume of a rock sample that is composed of pore spaces or voids. See porosity.',l:''},'absolute pressure':{d:'total pressure measured from an absolute vacuum. It equals the sum of the gauge pressure and the atmospheric pressure corresponding to the barometer (expressed in pound per square inch).',l:''},'absolute temperature scale':{d:'a scale temperature measurement in which zero degrees is absolute zero. On the Rankin absolute temperature scale, in which degrees correspond to degrees Fahrenheit, water freezes at 492 degrees and boils at 672 degrees. On the Kelvin absolute temperature scale, in which degrees correspond to degrees Celsius, water freezes at 273 degrees and boils at 373 degrees. See absolute zero.',l:''},'absolute zero':{d:'a hypothetical temperature at which there is a total absence of heat. Since heat is a result of energy caused by molecular motion, there is no motion of molecules with respect to each other at absolute zero.',l:''},'acceptance criteria':{d:'defined limits placed on characteristics of materials, products, or services. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'accumulate':{d:'to amass or collect. When oil and gas migrate into porous formations, the quantity collected is called an accumulation.',l:''},'accumulator':{d:'the storage device on a drilling rig for nitrogen-pressurized hydraulic fluid, which is used to close blowout preventers',l:''},'accumulator bank':{d:'an assemblage of multiple accumulators sharing a common manifold. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'accumulator precharge':{d:'an initial nitrogen charge in an accumulator which is further compressed when the hydraulic fluid is pumped into the accumulator storing potential energy.',l:''},'ACE':{d:'Axial Compliant Expansion (running tool)',l:''},'acidity':{d:'the quality of being an acid. Relative acid strength of a liquid is measured by pH. a liquid with a pH below 7 is an acid. See pH value',l:''},'acoustic control system':{d:'a subsea control system that uses coded acoustic signals communication. An acoustic control system is normally used as an emergency backup, having control of a few selected critical functions.',l:''},'ACP':{d:'Annulus Casing Packer (Inflatable Packer product line)',l:''},'actuation test':{d:'the closing and opening of a Blowout Preventer unit to assure mechanical functionality.',l:''},'actuator':{d:'a device used to open or close a valve by means of applied manual, hydraulic, pneumatic, or electric energy',l:''},'adapter':{d:'a pressure containing piece of equipment having API end connections of different nominal sizes and/or pressure ratings, used to connect other pieces of equipment of different API nominal sizes and/or pressure ratings.',l:''},'adapter spool':{d:'a joint to connect Blowout Preventers of different sizes or pressure ratings to the casing head.',l:''},'adjustable choke':{d:'a choke in which the position of a conical needle or sleeve may be changed with respect to its sea, to vary the rate of flow; may be manual or automatic. See choke',l:''},'aerated fluid':{d:'drilling fluid injected with air or gas in varying amounts for the purpose of reducing hydrostatic head.',l:''},'AH':{d:'Along Hole (same as AHD and MD, Measured Depth)',l:''},'AHBKB':{d:'Along Hole Below Kelly Bushing',l:''},'AHD':{d:'Along Hole Depth',l:''},'air drilling':{d:'a method of rotary drilling that uses compressed air as the circulation medium',l:''},'air gap':{d:'the distance from the normal level of the sea surface to the bottom of the hull or base of an offshore drilling platform.',l:''},'air-actuated':{d:'powered by compressed air, for example, the clutch and the brake system in drilling equipment.',l:''},'air/gas drilling':{d:'refer to aerated fluid air pump/air powered pump n: air driven hydraulic piston pump. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'alkali':{d:'a substance having marked basic (alkaline) properties, such as a hydroxide of an alkali metal. See base.',l:''},'alkalinity':{d:'the combining power of a base, or alkali as measured by the number of equivalents of an acid with which it reacts to form a salt. Measured by pH alkalinity is possessed by any solution that has a pH greater than 7. See pH value.',l:''},'ALS':{d:'Artificial Lift Systems',l:''},'American Petroleum Institute':{d:'founded in 1920, this national oil trade organisation is the leading standardising organisation for oil field drilling and producing equipment. It maintains departments of transportation, refining, and marketing in Washington, DC, and a department of production in Dallas.',l:''},'American Society for Testing and Materials':{d:'an organisation, based in Philadelphia, which sets guidelines for testing ad use of equipment and materials.',l:''},'American Society of Mechanical Engineers':{d:'a New York City-based organisation whose equipment standard are sometimes used by the oil industry. Its official publication is Mechanical Engineering.',l:''},'anchor':{d:'any device that secures or fastens equipment. In down hole equipment, the term often refers to the tail pipe. In offshore drilling, floating drilling vessels are often secured over drill sites by large metal anchors like those used on ships.',l:''},'anchor buoy':{d:'a floating marker used in a spread mooring system to position each anchor of a semi-submersible rig or drill ship.',l:''},'angle of deflection':{d:'in directional drilling, the angle, expressed in degrees, at which a well is deflected from the vertical by a whipstock or other deflecting tool.',l:''},'angle of deviation':{d:'also called drift angle and angle of drift. See deviation.',l:''},'annular blowout preventer':{d:'a large valve with a generally thyroidal shaped steel reinforced elastomer packing element that is hydraulic operated to close and seal around any drill pipe size or to provide full closure of the well bore. Usually installed above the ram preventers, it forms a seal in the annular space between the pipe and the well bore, or, if no pipe is present, on the well bore itself.',l:''},'annular packing element':{d:'a rubber/steel unit that effects a seal in an annular preventer or diverter. The annular packing element is displaced toward the bore centre by the upward movement of an annular piston',l:''},'annular sealing device':{d:'generally, a torus shaped steel housing containing an annular packing element which facilitates closure of the annulus by constricting to seal on the pipe or Kelly in the well bore. Some annular sealing devices also facilitate shutoff of the open hole.',l:''},'annular space':{d:'1. The space surrounding a cylindrical object within a cylinder. 2. The space around a pipe in a well bore, the outer wall of which may be the wall of either the borehole or the casing; sometimes termed the annulus.',l:''},'annular velocity':{d:'the rate at which fluid is travelling in the annular space of a drilling well',l:''},'annulus':{d:'the space around a pipe in a wellbore, the outer wall of which may be the wall of the borehole or the casing',l:''},'annulus friction pressure':{d:'circulating pressure loss inherent in the annulus between the drill string and casing or open hole.',l:''},'anticlinal trap':{d:'a hydrocarbon trap in which petroleum accumulates in the top of an anticline. See anticline.',l:''},'anticline':{d:'an arched, inverted-trough configuration of folded and stratified rock layers.',l:''},'API':{d:'American Petroleum Institute',l:''},'API gravity':{d:'the measure of the density or gravity of liquid petroleum products, derived from specific gravity in accordance with the following equation: API gravity is expressed in degrees, a specific gravity of 10 being equivalent to 10° API.',l:''},'artificial lift':{d:'any method used to raise oil to the surface through a well after reservoir pressure has declined to the point at which the well no longer produces by means of natural energy. Sucker rod pumps, gas lifts, hydraulic pumps, and submersible electric pumps are the most common forms of artificial lift.',l:''},'AsiaPac':{d:'Asia Pacific Region',l:''},'ASME':{d:'American Society of Mechanical Engineers.',l:''},'astern':{d:'1. At or toward the stern of a ship or an offshore drilling rig; abaft. 2. Behind the ship or rig.',l:''},'ASTM':{d:'American Society for Testing and Materials.',l:''},'Atm':{d:'atmosphere',l:''},'atmosphere':{d:'a unit of pressure equal to the atmospheric pressure at sea level, 14.7 pounds per square inch (101.325 kPa). One Atmosphere is equal to 14.7 psi or 101.325 kPa.',l:''},'atmosphere absolute':{d:'total pressure at a depth underwater, expressed as multiples of normal atmospheric pressure.',l:''},'atmospheric pressure':{d:'the pressure exerted by the weight of the atmosphere. At sea level, the pressure is approximately 14.7 psi (101.325 kPa), often referred to as 1 atmosphere.',l:''},'attapulgite':{d:'a fibrous clay mineral that is viscosity-building substance, used principally in saltwater-base drilling fluids.',l:''},'automatic choke':{d:'an adjustable choke that is power-operated to control pressure or flow. See adjustable choke.',l:''},'automatic control':{d:'a device that regulates various factors (such as flow rate, pressure, or temperature) of a system without supervision or operation by personnel. See instrumentation.',l:''},'automatic driller':{d:'a mechanism used to regulate the amount of weight on the bit without requiring attendance by personnel. Automatic Drillers free the driller from the sometimes tedious task of manipulating the draw-works brake in order to maintain correct weight on the bit. Also called an automatic drilling control unit.',l:''},'automatic fill-up shoe':{d:'a device that is installed on the first joint of casing and that automatically regulates the amount of fluid in the casing. The valve in this shoe keeps fluid from entering the casing until fluid pressure causes the valve to open, allowing fluid to enter the casing.',l:''},'automatic gauge':{d:'an instrument installed on the outside of a tank to permit observation of the depth of the liquid inside.',l:''},'automatic slips':{d:'a device, operated by air or hydraulic fluid, that fits into the opening in the rotary table when the drill stem must be suspended in the well bore (as when a connection or trip is being made). Automatic slips, also called power slips, eliminate the need for roughneck\u0027s to set and take out slips manually. See slips.',l:''},'auxiliary brake':{d:'a braking mechanism, supplemental to the mechanical brake, that permits the safe lowering of heavy hook loads at retarded rates, without incurring appreciable brake maintenance. There are two types of auxiliary brakes - the hydrodynamic and the electro-dynamic. In both types, work is converted in to heat which is dissipated through liquid cooling systems.',l:''},'average radial stress':{d:'the stress in tubular radial direction averaged along the cylindrical component wall thickness',l:''},'axial load':{d:'the force acting along the longitudinal axis of the tubular',l:''},'axial stress':{d:'arises from the force vector component perpendicular to the material cross section on which it acts',l:''},'AZD':{d:'azimuthal density',l:''},'azimuth':{d:'compass direction of the wellbore at the specified MD, relative to true north',l:''},'B/D':{d:'barrels per day',l:''},'back off':{d:'to unscrew one threaded piece (such as a section of pipe) from another.',l:''},'back pressure valve':{d:'a valve that permits flow in only one direction',l:''},'back-off joint':{d:'a section of pipe with left-hand threads on one end and conventional right-hand threads on the other. In setting a liner, a back-off joint is attached to it so that the drill pipe may be disengaged from the liner by conventional right-hand rotation.',l:''},'back-pressure':{d:'1. The pressure maintained on equipment or systems through which a fluid flows. 2. In reference to engines, a term used to describe the resistance to the flow of exhaust gas through the exhaust pipe.',l:''},'backup tongs':{d:'the tongs used to back up the drill pipe as it is being made up into or taken out of the drill system.',l:''},'baffle plate':{d:'1. A partial restriction, generally a plate, placed to change the direction, guide the flow, or promote mixing within the tank or vessel. 2. A device that is seated on the bit pin, in a tool joint, or in a drill pipe float, used to centralise the lower end of a go-devil while permitting the bypass of drilling fluid. The go-devil while permitting the bypass of drilling fluid. The go-devil contains a surveying instrument.',l:''},'bail':{d:'a cylindrical steel bar (similar in form to the handle or bail of a bucket, but much larger) that supports the swivel and connects it to the hook. Sometimes, the two cylindrical bars that support the elevators and attach them to the hook are also called bails or links. v: to recover bottomhole fluids, samples, fluid, sand, or drill cuttings by lowering a cylindrical vessel called a bailer to the bottom of a well, filling it, and retrieving it.',l:''},'bailer':{d:'a long cylindrical container, fitted with a valve at its lower end, used to remove water, sand, fluid, drill cuttings, or oil from a well.',l:''},'ball valve':{d:'a valve which employs a rotating ball to open or close the flow passage.',l:''},'barge':{d:'any one of many types of flat-decked, shallow-draft vessels, usually towed by a boat. A complete drilling rig may be assembled on a drilling barge, which usually is submersible; that is, it has a submersible hull or base that is flooded with water at the drilling site. Drilling equipment and crew quarters are mounted on a superstructure above the water level.',l:''},'barite':{d:'barium Sulphate, BaSO4; a mineral frequently used to increase the weight or density of drilling fluid. Its specific gravity or relative density is 4.2 (i.e. it is 4.2 times heavier or denser than water. See barium Sulphate and fluid.',l:''},'barite plug':{d:'a settled volume of barite particles from a barite slurry placed in the well bore to seal off a pressurised zone.',l:''},'barium sulphate':{d:'a chemical compound of barium, Sulphur, and oxygen (BaSO4. It may form a tenacious scale that is very difficult to remove. Also called barite.',l:''},'barrel':{d:'a measure of volume of petroleum products in the United States. One barrel is the equivalent of 42 US gallons or 0.15899 cubic metres. One cubic metre equals 6.2897 barrels.',l:''},'barrels per day':{d:'in the United States, a measure of the rate of flow of a well; the total amount of oil and other fluids produced or processed per day.',l:''},'baryte':{d:'variation of barite. See barite.',l:''},'base':{d:'a substance capable of reacting with an acid to form a salt. A typical base is sodium hydroxide (caustic), with the chemical formula NaOH. For example, sodium hydroxide combines with hydrochloric acid to form sodium chloride (a salt) and water; this reaction is written chemically as NaOH + HCl → NaCl + H20',l:''},'basement rock':{d:'either igneous or metamorphic rock, seldom containing petroleum. Ordinarily it lies below sedimentary rock. When it is encountered in drilling, the well is usually abandoned.',l:''},'basin':{d:'a cylindrical structure in the subsurface, formerly the bed of an ancient sea. Because it is composed of sedimentary rock and because its contours provide traps for petroleum, a basin is a good prospect for exploration. For example, the Permian Basin in West Texas is a major oil producer.',l:''},'battery':{d:'1. An installation of identical or nearly identical pieces of equipment (such as a tank battery or a battery of meters). 2. An electricity storage device.',l:''},'BB':{d:'Blind Box – slickline tool to act as downhole “hammer”',l:''},'bbl':{d:'barrel, the standard oil measurement of 42 US gallons',l:''},'bbl/d':{d:'barrels per day',l:''},'Bcf':{d:'billion cubic feet',l:''},'Bcf/d':{d:'billion cubic feet per day',l:''},'bed':{d:'a specific layer of earth or rock, presenting a contrast to other layers of different material lying above, below, or adjacent to it.',l:''},'bedding plane':{d:'the surface that separates each successive layer of a stratified rock from its preceding layer.',l:''},'bell nipple':{d:'a short length of pipe (a nipple) installed on top of the Blowout Preventer. The top end of the nipple is expanded, or belled, to guide drill tools into the hole and usually has side connections for the fill line and fluid line.',l:''},'bending stress':{d:'The tensile or compressive stress resulting from the application of a non-axial force on a structural member. Bending stress is a more specific type of normal stress.',l:''},'bent housing':{d:'a special housing for the positive displacement down hole fluid motor that is manufactured with a bend of 1-3 degrees to facilitate directional drilling.',l:''},'bent sub':{d:'a short, cylindrical device installed in the drillstring between the last drill collar and a downhole fluid motor. The purpose of a bent sub is to deflect the fluid motor off vertical to drill a directional hole',l:''},'bentonite':{d:'a colloidal clay, composed primarily of montmorillonite, that swells when wet. Because of its gel-forming properties, bentonite is a major component of drilling fluids. See gel.',l:''},'BFPH':{d:'barrels of fluid per hour; used in drilling reports',l:''},'BHA':{d:'bottomhole assembly',l:''},'BHP':{d:'bottom hole pressure',l:''},'BHT':{d:'bottom hole temperature',l:''},'bit':{d:'the cutting of boring element used in drilling oil and gas wells. The bit consists of a cutting element and a circulating element. The circulating element permits the passage of drilling fluid and utilises the hydraulic force of the fluid to improve drilling rates. In rotary drilling, several drill collars are joined to the bottom end of the drill pipe column, and the bit is attached to the end of the string of drill collars. Most bits used in rotary drilling are roller cone bits, but diamond bits are also used extensively. See roller cone bit and diamond bit.',l:''},'bit breaker':{d:'a heavy plate that fits in the rotary table and holds the drill bit while it is being made up in, or broken out of, the drill stem. See bit.',l:''},'bit gauge':{d:'a circular ring used to determine whether a bit is of the correct outside diameter. Bit gauges are often used to determine whether the bit has been worn down to a diameter smaller than specifications allow; such a bit is described as under-gauge.',l:''},'bit-sub':{d:'a sub inserted between the drill collar and the bit.',l:''},'BJ':{d:'Blast Joint',l:''},'blank casing':{d:'casing without perforations',l:''},'blank flange':{d:'a solid disk used to dead-end, or close off, a companion flange.',l:''},'blast hole drilling':{d:'the drilling of holes into the earth for the purpose of placing a blasting charge (such as dynamite) in them.',l:''},'bleed':{d:'to drain off liquid or gas, generally slowly, through a valve called a bleeder. To bleed down',l:''},'blind drilling':{d:'a drilling operation in which the drilling fluid is not returned to the surface. Sometimes blind-drilling techniques are resorted to when lost circulation occurs.',l:''},'blind ram':{d:'an integral part of a Blowout Preventer that serves as the closing element on an open hole. Its ends do not fit around the drill pipe but seal against each other and shut off the space below completely. See ram.',l:''},'blind ram preventer':{d:'a Blowout Preventer in which blind rams are the closing elements.',l:''},'blind/shear rams':{d:'blind rams with a built-in cutting edge that will shear tubulars that may be in the hole, thus allowing the blind rams to seal the hole. Used primarily in subsea systems. (API Recommended Practice 53)',l:''},'block':{d:'any assembly of pulleys, a common framework; in mechanics, one or more pulleys, or sheaves, mounted to rotate on a common axis. The crown block is an assembly of sheaves mounted on beams at the top of the derrick. The drilling line is reeved over the sheaves of the crown block alternately with the sheaves of the travelling block, which is raised and lowered in the derrick by the drilling line. When elevators are attached to a hook on the travelling block and drill pipe latched in the elevators, the pipe can be raised or lowered.',l:''},'block position':{d:'the centre position of a three-position control valve.',l:''},'blooey line':{d:'the discharge pipe from a well being drilled by air drilling. The blooey line is used to conduct the air gas used for circulation away from the rig to reduce the fire hazard as well as to transport the cuttings a suitable distance from the well. See formation pressure and kick.',l:''},'blowout':{d:'an uncontrolled flow of gas, oil, or other well fluids into the atmosphere. A blowout, or gusher, can occur when formation pressure exceeds the pressure applied to it by the amount of drilling fluid. A kick warns of an impending blowout. See formation pressure and kick.',l:''},'blowout preventer':{d:'one of several valves installed at the wellhead to prevent the escape of pressure, either in the annulus between the casing and drillpipe or in openhole during drilling completion operations',l:''},'blowout preventer control panel':{d:'a set of controls, usually located near the drillers position on the rig floor, that is manipulated to open and close the Blowout Preventers.',l:''},'blowout preventer control unit':{d:'a service that stores hydraulic fluid under pressure in special containers and provides a method to open and close the Blowout Preventers quickly and reliably. Usually, compressed air and hydraulic pressure provide the opening and closing force in the unit.',l:''},'blowout preventer drill':{d:'a training procedure to determine that rig crews are familiar with correct operating practices to be followed in the use of blowout prevention equipment. A \"dry run\" of blowout prevention action.',l:''},'blowout preventer stack':{d:'the assembly of well control equipment, including preventers, spools, valves and nipples connected to the top of the casing-head.',l:''},'blowout preventer test tool':{d:'a tool to allow pressure testing of the Blowout Preventer stack and accessory equipment by sealing the well bore immediately below the stack.',l:''},'body':{d:'any portion of API equipment between end connection, with or without internal parts, which contains well bore pressure',l:''},'boiling point':{d:'the temperature at which the vapour pressure of a liquid becomes equal to the pressure exerted on the liquid by the surrounding atmosphere. The boiling point of water is 212(F or 100(C at atmospheric pressure (14.7 psig or 101.325 kPa).',l:''},'boll weevil':{d:'an inexperienced rig or oil field worker; sometimes shortened to weevil.',l:''},'boll weevil corner':{d:'the work station of an inexperienced rotary helper, on the opposite side of the rotary from the pipe tracker.',l:''},'bolting':{d:'threaded fasteners (studs, nuts, bolts and cap-screws) used to assemble pressure containing parts or join end or outlet connections.',l:''},'BOP':{d:'blowout preventer',l:''},'BOP closing ratio (Ram BOP)':{d:'a dimension-less factor equal to the well bore pressure divided by the operating pressure necessary to close a Ram BOP against well bore pressure. Usually calculated for maximum rated well bore pressure.',l:''},'BOP section':{d:'one of the sections in Interval 0 created for all rig types. The BOP section represents the structural casing that the blowout preventer and wellhead are installed on.',l:''},'BOP stack maximum rated well bore pressure':{d:'the pressure containment rating of the ram Blowout Preventer\u0027s in a stack. In the event that the rams are rated at different pressures, the Blowout Preventer Stack Maximum Rated Well bore Pressure is considered equal to the lowest rated ram Blowout Preventer pressure. In stacks which do not contain any ram Blowout Preventer, the Blowout Preventer stack maximum rated well bore pressure is considered equal to the lowest rated Blowout Preventer pressure.',l:''},'BOPD':{d:'barrels of oil per day',l:''},'BOPE':{d:'an abbreviation for Blowout Preventer equipment.',l:''},'bore':{d:'1. The inside diameter of a pipe or a drilled hole. 2. The diameter of the cylinder of an engine.',l:''},'borehole':{d:'the well bore; the hole made by drilling or boring. See well bore.',l:''},'borehole pressure':{d:'total pressure exerted in the well bore by a column of fluid and/or back pressure imposed at the surface. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'bottom hole':{d:'the lowest or deepest part of a well. adj.: pertaining to the bottom of the well bore.',l:''},'bottom hole assembly':{d:'the portion of the drilling assembly below the drill pipe. It can be very simple - composed of only the bit and drill collars - or it can be very complex and made up of several drilling tools.',l:''},'bottom hole pressure':{d:'1. the pressure at the bottom of a borehole. It is caused by the hydrostatic pressure of the drilling fluid in the hole and, sometimes, any back-pressure held at the surface, as when the well is shut in with a Blowout Preventer. When fluid is being circulated, bottom hole pressure is the hydrostatic pressure plus the remaining circulating pressure required to move the fluid up the annulus. 2. the pressure in a well at a point opposite the producing formation, as recorded by a bottom hole pressure bomb.',l:''},'bottom hole pressure bomb':{d:'a bomb used to record the pressure in a well at a point opposite the producing formation.',l:''},'bottom hole temperature':{d:'temperature measured in a well at a depth at the midpoint of the thickness of the producing zone.',l:''},'bottom-supported drilling vessels':{d:'offshore drilling vessels which float to the desired drilling location and are either ballasted or jacked up so that the vessel is supported by the ocean floor while in the drilling mode. Rigs of this type include platform, submersibles, swamp barges and jack-up drilling rigs. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'bottoms up':{d:'a complete trip from the bottom of the well bore to the top.',l:''},'bottoms-up gas':{d:'gas that has risen to the surface from previously drilled gas bearing formations. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'bourdon tube':{d:'a flattened metal tube bent in a curve, which tends to straighten when pressure is applied internally. By the movements of an indicator over a circular scale, a Bourdon tube indicates the pressure applied.',l:''},'box':{d:'the female section of a connection. See tool joint.',l:''},'box and pin':{d:'See tool joint.',l:''},'Boyle\u0027s law':{d:'a gas law that concerns pressure. It states that for any ideal gas or mixture of ideal gases at any definite temperature, the product of the absolute pressure times the volume is a constant (PV = K)',l:''},'BPH':{d:'barrels per hour; used in drilling reports.',l:''},'BPLD':{d:'barrels of liquid per day, usually used in reference to total production of oil and water from a well.',l:''},'BPV':{d:'Back Pressure Valve',l:''},'Bradenhead':{d:'casing head.',l:''},'Bradenhead flange':{d:'a flanged connection at the top of the oil well casing.',l:''},'Bradenhead squeezing':{d:'the process by which hydraulic pressure is applied to a well to force fluid or cement outside the well bore without the use of a packer. The Bradenhead, or casing head, is closed to shut off the annulus when making a Bradenhead squeeze. Although this term is still used, the term Bradenhead is obsolete. See annular space and casing head and squeeze.',l:''},'brake':{d:'a device for arresting the motion of a mechanism, usually by means of friction, as in the draw-works brake.',l:''},'brake band':{d:'a part of the brake mechanism, consisting of a flexible steel band line with asbestos or a similar material, that grips a drum when tightened. On a drilling rig, the brake band acts on the flanges of the draw-works drum to control the lowering of the travelling block and its load of drill pipe, casing, or tubing.',l:''},'brake block':{d:'a section of the lining of a band brake; it is shaped to conform to the curvature of the band and is attached to it with countersunk screws. See brake band.',l:''},'break circulation':{d:'to start the fluid pump for restoring circulation column. As the stagnant drilling fluid has thickened or gelled during the period of no circulation, a high pump pressure is usually required to break circulation.',l:''},'break out':{d:'1. To unscrew one section of pipe from another section, especially drill pipe while it is being withdrawn from the well bore. During this operation, the tongs are used to start the unscrewing operation. 2. To separate, as gas from a liquid or water from an emulsion.',l:''},'breaking strength':{d:'the load under which a chain or rope breaks.',l:''},'breathe':{d:'to move with a slight, regular rhythm. Breathing occurs in tanks of vessels when vapours are expelled and air is taken in. For example, a tank of crude oil expands because of the rise in temperature during the day and contracts as it cools at night, expelling vapours as it expands and taking in air as it contracts. Tubing breathes when it moves up and down in sequence with a sucker rod pump.',l:''},'breather':{d:'a small vent in an otherwise airtight enclosure for maintaining equality of pressure within and without.',l:''},'bridge':{d:'1. An obstruction in the borehole, usually caused by the caving in of the wall of the borehole or by the intrusion of a larger boulder. 2. A tool placed in the hole to retain cement or other material that may later be removed, drilled out, or permanently.',l:''},'bridge plug':{d:'a down hole tool, composed primarily of slips, a plug mandrel, and a rubber sealing element, that is run and set in casing to isolate a lower zone while an upper section is being tested or cemented.',l:''},'bridging material':{d:'the fibrous, flaky or granular material added to cement slurry or drilling fluid to aid in sealing formations in which lost circulation has occurred. See lost circulation and lost circulation material.',l:''},'brine':{d:'water that has a large quantity of salt, especially sodium chloride, dissolved in it; salt water.',l:''},'bring in a well':{d:'to complete a well and put on producing status.',l:''},'broaching':{d:'venting of fluids to the surface or to the seabed through channels external to the casing. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'BRT':{d:'Below Rotary Table',l:''},'Bscf/d':{d:'billion standard cubic feet per day.',l:''},'Btu':{d:'British thermal unit.',l:''},'bubble point':{d:'1. The temperature and pressure at which part of a liquid begins to convert to gas. For example, if a certain volume of liquid is held at constant pressure, but its temperature is increased, a point is reached when bubbles of gas begin to form in the liquid. That is the bubble point. 2. The temperature and pressure at which gas, held in solution in crude oil, breaks out of solution as free gas.',l:''},'buckling contact force':{d:'additional contact force due to drillstring helical buckling',l:''},'buckling stress':{d:'bending of the pipe which may occur due to deviation of the hole. The pipe may bend because of the angle of the hole or because of an abrupt deviation such as a dog leg.',l:''},'building test':{d:'a test in which a well is shut in for a prescribed period of time and a bottom hole pressure bomb run in the well to record the pressure. From this data and from the knowledge of pressures in a nearby well, the effectiveness drainage radius or the presence of permeability barriers or other production deterrents surrounding the well bore can be estimated.',l:''},'bull plug':{d:'a threaded nipple with a rounded closed end, used to stop up a hole or close off the end of a line.',l:''},'bullet perforator':{d:'a tubular device that, when lowered to a selected depth within a well, fire bullets through the casing to provide hole through which the formation fluids may enter the well bore.',l:''},'bullhead squeezing':{d:'the process by which hydraulic pressure is applied to a well to force fluid such as cement outside the well bore. Annular flow (returns) is prevented by a packer set in the casing above the perforations and/or in open hole. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'bumpless transfer':{d:'the transfer from main electrical supply to an alternate power supply without losing signal and/or memory circuit normally associated with poser interruption. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'buoyancy':{d:'the apparent loss of weight of an object immersed in a fluid. If the object is floating, the immersed portion displaces a volume of liquid the weight of which is equal to the weight of the object.',l:''},'bypass valve':{d:'a valve that permits flow around a control valve, apiece of equipment, or a system.',l:''},'C':{d:'Centigrade ( oC )',l:''},'calculated value':{d:'An intermediate value derived from other properties',l:''},'calibration':{d:'comparison and adjustment to a standard of known accuracy. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'cap a well':{d:'to control a blowout by placing a very strong valve on the well head. See blowout.',l:''},'cap rock':{d:'1. Impermeable rock overlying an oil or gas reservoir. 2. The porous and permeable strata overlying salt domes that may serve as the reservoir rock.',l:''},'carbon dioxide':{d:'a colourless, odourless gaseous compound of carbon and oxygen (CO2). A product of combustion and a filler for fire extinguishers, this heavier-than-air gas can collect in low-lying areas where it may displace oxygen and present the hazard of anoxia.',l:''},'carbon monoxide':{d:'a colourless, odourless gaseous compound of carbon and oxygen (CO). A product of incomplete combustion, it is extremely poisonous to breathe.',l:''},'cascade system':{d:'in respiratory systems, a series connection of air cylinders in which the output of air from one adds to that of the next.',l:''},'case-hardened':{d:'hardened (as for a ferrous alloy) so that the surface layer is harder than the interior.',l:''},'cased':{d:'pertaining to a well bore in which casing has been run and cemented.',l:''},'cased hole':{d:'a well bore in which casing has been run.',l:''},'casing':{d:'steel pipe placed in an oil or gas well as drilling progresses, to prevent the wall of the hole from caving in during drilling, to prevent seepage of fluids, and to provide a means of extracting petroleum if the well is productive.',l:''},'casing hanger':{d:'a circular device with a frictional gripping arrangement, used to suspend casing in a well.',l:''},'casing pressure':{d:'the pressure built up in a well between the casing and tubing or the casing and drill pipe.',l:''},'casing seat test':{d:'a procedure whereby the formation immediately below the casing shoe is subjected to a pressure equal to the pressure expected to be exerted later by a higher drilling fluid density and back pressure created by a kick. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'casing section':{d:'the portion of the well that is lined with casing, which is cemented in place and typically extends to the surface',l:''},'casing shoe':{d:'the rounded concrete bottom end of a string casing. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'casing string':{d:'the entire length of all the joints of casing run in well. Casing is manufactured in lengths of about 30 feet (9 metres), each length or joint being joined to another as casing is run as well.',l:''},'casing-head/spool':{d:'a heavy, flanged steel fitting connected to the first string of casing. It provides a housing for slips and packing assemblies, allows suspension of intermediate and production strings of casing and supplies the means for the annulus to be sealed off. Also called a spool.',l:''},'casting':{d:'1. An object at or near finished shape obtained by solidification of a substance in a mould. v. 2. Pouring molten metal into a mould to produce an object of desired shape. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'catalyst':{d:'a substance that alters, accelerates, or instigates chemical reactions without itself being affected.',l:''},'cathode':{d:'1. One of two electrodes in an electrolytic cell, represented as the positive terminal of a cell. 2. In cathodic protection systems, the protected structure that is representative of the cathode and is protected by having a conventional current flow from an anode to the structure through the electrolyte.',l:''},'caustic soda':{d:'sodium hydroxide, used to maintain an alkaline pH in drilling fluid and in petroleum fractions. Its formula is NaOH.',l:''},'caving':{d:'collapsing of the walls of the well bore, also called sloughing.',l:''},'CBL':{d:'Cement Bond Log',l:''},'cc':{d:'cubic centimetre.',l:''},'CCL':{d:'Casing Collar Locator',l:''},'CCP':{d:'Circulating Casing Pressure',l:''},'Celsius scale':{d:'the metric scale of temperature measurement used universally by scientists. On this scale, 0 degrees represents the freezing point of water and 100 degrees its boiling point at a barometric pressure of 760 mm. Degrees Celsius are converted to degrees Fahrenheit by using the following equation: (F = 9/5 x (°C) + 32 The Celsius scale was formerly called the centigrade scale, now, however, the term Celsius is preferred in the International System of Units (SI).',l:''},'cement plug':{d:'a portion of cement placed at some point in the well bore to seal it.',l:''},'CFG':{d:'cubic feet of gas, used in drilling reports.',l:''},'change rams':{d:'to take rams out of a Blowout Preventer and replace them with rams of a different size or type. When the size of a drill pipe is changed, the size of the pipe rams must be changed to ensure that they seal around the pipe when closed.',l:''},'channelling':{d:'the bypassing of oil in a water-drive field due to erratic or uncontrolled water encroachment. The natural tendency toward channelling is aggravated by excessive production rates, which encourage premature water encroachment.',l:''},'Charle\u0027s law':{d:'a gas law that states that at constant pressure the volume of a fixed mass or quantity of gas varies directly with the absolute temperature.',l:''},'CHC':{d:'Cased Hole Completions',l:''},'check valve':{d:'a valve that permits flow in one direction only. Commonly referred to as a one-way valve. If the gas or liquid starts to reverse, the valve automatically closes, preventing reverse movement.',l:''},'chemical analysis':{d:'determination of the chemical composition of material. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'chert':{d:'a quartzitic rock with hardness equal to or harder than flint.',l:''},'CHF ':{d:'Casing Head Flange',l:''},'CHH':{d:'Casing Head Housing',l:''},'child interval':{d:'One or more intervals that are contained by a parent interval.',l:''},'choke':{d:'a device with an orifice installed in a line to restrict the flow of fluids. Surface chokes are a part of the Christmas tree on a well and contain a choke nipple, or bean, with a small-diameter bore that serves to restrict the flow. Chokes are also used to control the rate of flow of the drilling fluid out of the hole when the well is closed in the Blowout Preventer and a kick is being circulated out of the hole.',l:''},'choke and kill valves':{d:'BOP stack mounted valves which are connected below the BOPs to allow access to the well bore to either choke or kill the well. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'choke line':{d:'a high pressure line connected below a BOP to direct well fluids from annulus to the choke manifold during well control operations.',l:''},'choke manifold':{d:'the arrangement of piping and special valves, called chokes, through which drilling fluid is circulated when the Blowout Preventers are closed and which is used to control the pressures encountered during a kick. See Blowout Preventer.',l:''},'CHP ':{d:'Casing Head Pressure',l:''},'Christmas tree':{d:'the control valves, pressure gauges and chokes assembled at the top of a well to control the flow of oil and gas after the well has been drilled and completed.',l:''},'CHS ':{d:'Casing Head Spool',l:''},'CIM ':{d:'Chemical Injection Mandrel',l:''},'circulate':{d:'to pass from one point throughout a system and back to the starting point. For example, drilling fluid is circulated out of the suction pit, down the drill pipe and drill collars, out the bit, up the annulus and back to the pits while drilling proceeds.',l:''},'circulate-and-weight method':{d:'a method of killing well pressure in which circulation is commenced immediately and fluid weight is brought up gradually, according to a definite schedule. Also called concurrent method.',l:''},'circulating device':{d:'a flow control device such as a sliding sleeve or side pocket mandrel, which is run on production/injection tubing for the purpose of establishing communications between tubing and the tubing annulus. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'circulating fluid':{d:'also called drilling fluid. See drilling fluid.',l:''},'Circulating head':{d:'a device attached to the top drill pipe or tubing to allow pumping into the well without use of the Kelly. (API Recommended Practice 59). ',l:''},'Circulating pressure':{d:'the pressure generated by the fluid pumps and exerted on the drill stem.',l:''},'circumferential average stress':{d:'the average force exerted circumferentially (perpendicular both to the axis and to the radius of the object) in both directions on every particle in the cylinder wall; also called average hoop stress',l:''},'CIS':{d:'Commonwealth of Independent States (old USSR)',l:''},'CITHP':{d:'Closed In Tubing Head Pressure',l:''},'CIV ':{d:'Completion Interval Valve',l:''},'Clamp connection':{d:'a pressure sealing device used to join two items without using conventional bolted flange joints. The two items to be sealed are prepared with clamp hubs. These hubs are held together by a clamp containing two to four bolts. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'client office':{d:'the location of the local office for the client company. Generally, this will be the office where the primary contact is located. Client offices can only be associated with one legal entity. The list of available client offices is filtered by the selected region, country, legal entity, and state.',l:''},'close in':{d:'1. To temporarily shut in a well that is capable of producing oil or gas. 2. To close the Blowout Preventers on a well to control a kick. The Blowout Preventers close off the annulus so that pressure from below cannot flow to the surface.',l:''},'Closed loop circuit':{d:'a hydraulic control circuit in which spent fluid is returned to the reservoir. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'closed-in pressure':{d:'See formation pressure.',l:''},'closing ratio':{d:'the ratio between the pressure in the hole and the operating-piston pressure needed to close the rams of a Blowout Preventer.',l:''},'closing unit (closing system)':{d:'the assembly of pumps, valves, line, accumulators, and other items necessary to open and close the Blowout Preventer equipment. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'Closing-unit pump':{d:'term for an electric or hydraulic pump on an accumulator, serving to pump hydraulic fluid under high pressure to the Blowout Preventers so that the preventers may be closed or opened.',l:''},'Closure bolting':{d:'fasteners used to assemble API Spec 16A equipment other than end and outlet connections. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'cm':{d:'centimeter',l:''},'CNR ':{d:'Canadian National Resources',l:''},'collapse pressure':{d:'the amount of force needed to crush the sides of pipe until it caves in on itself. Collapse occurs when the pressure outside the pipe is greater than the pressure inside the pipe.',l:''},'come out of the hole':{d:'to pull the drill stem out of the well bore. This withdrawal is necessary to change the bit, change from a core barrel to the bit, run electric logs, prepare for a drill stem test, run casing, and so on.',l:''},'company man':{d:'also called company representative.',l:''},'company representative':{d:'an employee of an operating company whose job is to represent the company’s interests at the drilling location.',l:''},'compressibility factor':{d:'a factor, usually expressed as Z, which gives the ratio of the actual volume of gas at a given temperature and pressure to the volume of gas when calculated by the ideal gas law without any consideration of the compressibility factor.',l:''},'concentric operations':{d:'well operations conducted using small diameter tubing inside conventional tubing or tubing-less completion’s, normally with the Christmas tree in place and using a small rig or hoisting unit. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'conductor casing – floating installations':{d:'the first string of pipe installed below the structural casing on which the well head and Blowout Preventer equipment are installed. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'conductor casing – onshore and bottom supported offshore installations':{d:'a relatively short string of large diameter pipe which is set to keep the top of the hole and provide a means of returning the up-flow drilling fluid from the well bore to the surface drilling fluid system onshore and bottom supported offshore installations. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'conductor pipe':{d:'1. A short string of large diameter casing used to keep the well bore open and to provide a means of conveying the up-flowing drilling fluid from the well bore to the fluid pit. 2. A boot.',l:''},'conductor section':{d:'one of the sections in Interval 0 created for all rig types, except drillship and semi-submersible rigs. The conductor section represents the conductor casing (also called a boot) installed below the BOP, used to keep the top of the wellbore open and to return drilling fluid from the wellbore to the surface.',l:''},'confined compressive strength':{d:'the constrained rock strength of the formation',l:''},'conformance':{d:'compliance with specified requirements. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'constant choke-pressure method':{d:'a method of killing a well that has kicked, in which the choke size is adjusted to maintain a constant casing pressure. This method does not work unless the kick is all or nearly all salt water, if the kick is gas , this method will not maintain a constant bottom hole pressure because gas expands as it rises in the annulus.',l:''},'constant pit-level method':{d:'a method of killing a well in which the fluid level in the pit is held constant while the choke size is reduced and the pump speed increases to the point where the formation fractures or casing ruptures, and control of the well is lost.',l:''},'contact':{d:'the primary contact at the client company. Contacts can only be associated with one legal entity and client office.',l:''},'contact force':{d:'force that acts at the point of contact between two objects',l:''},'continental shelf':{d:'a zone, adjacent to a continent, that extends from the low waterline to the point at which the sea floor slopes off steeply to 600 feet (183 m) deep or more.',l:''},'continuous reeled tubing':{d:'tubing stored on a reel that can be run in and out of a well without making a connection. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'control fluid':{d:'hydraulic oil or water-based fluid which, under pressure, pilots the operation of control valves or directly operates functions. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'control hose bundle ':{d:'a group of pilot and signal hoses assembled into a bundle with an outer protective sheath. For subsea applications it may contain a hydraulic supply line. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'control line':{d:'a flexible hose or rigid line that transmits the hydraulic power fluid to a function. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'control manifold':{d:'the assemblage of valves, regulators, gauges and piping used to regulate pressures and control the flow of hydraulic power fluid to operate system functions. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'control panel':{d:'an enclosure displaying an array of switches, push buttons, lights and/or valves and various pressure gauges or meters to control or monitor functions. Control panel types include: diverter panel, Driller’s panel, master panel and mini or auxiliary remote panel. All these panels are remote from the main hydraulic manifold and can be pneumatic, electric or hydraulic powered. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'control pod':{d:'the assemblage of valves and pressure regulators which respond to control signals to direct hydraulic power fluid through assigned porting, to operate functions. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'control valve (subsea control system)':{d:'a pilot operated valve in the subsea control pod that directs power fluid pumps, rotary table and other equipment designed to perform well Workovers, re-Completions, and other work which requires removal of the Christmas tree and pulling or manipulation of the tubing. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'control valve (surface control system)':{d:'a valve mounted on the hydraulic manifold which directs hydraulic power fluid to the selected function (such as annular BOP close) while simultaneously venting the opposite function (annular BOP open). (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'core':{d:'a cylindrical sample taken form a formation for geological analysis. Usually a conventional core barrel is substituted for the bit and produces a sample as it penetrates the formation. v: to obtain a formation sample for analysis.',l:''},'core barrel':{d:'a tubular device, usually form 10 to 60 feet long, run at the bottom of the drill pipe in place of a bit and used to cut a core sample.',l:''},'corrosion resistant ring grooves':{d:'ring grooves lined with metal resistant to metal-loss corrosion. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'cp':{d:'centipoise',l:''},'CPS ':{d:'Completion Production Systems',l:''},'CRA ':{d:'Corrosion Resistant Alloys',l:''},'crew':{d:'the workers on a drilling or workover rig, including the Driller, Derrickman, and rotary helpers.',l:''},'critical point':{d:' 1. The point at which, in terms of temperature and pressure, a fluid cannot be distinguished as being either a gas or a liquid, the point at which the physical properties of a liquid and a gas are identical. 2. One of the places along the length of drilling line at which strain is exerted as pipe is run into or pulled out of the hole.',l:''},'critical pressure':{d:'the pressure needed to condense a vapour at its critical temperature.',l:''},'critical temperature':{d:'the highest temperature at which a substance can be separated into two fluid phases – liquid and vapour. Above the critical temperature, a gas cannot be liquefied by pressure alone.',l:''},'crossover sub':{d:'a sub used between two sizes or types of threads in the drill stem assembly.',l:''},'crude oil':{d:'unrefined liquid petroleum. It ranges in gravity from 9( API to 55( API and in colour from yellow to black, and it may have a paraffin, asphalt, or mixed base. If a crude oil, or crude, contains a sizeable amount of sulphur or sulphur compounds, it is called a sour crude, if it has little or no sulphur, it is called a sweet crude. In addition, crude oils may be referred to as heavy or light according to API gravity, the lighter oils having the higher gravity’s.',l:''},'CS ':{d:'Compression Services (ex Weatherford Division)',l:''},'CSG (csg) ':{d:'Casing',l:''},'CTU ':{d:'Coiled Tubing Unit',l:''},'cubic centimetres':{d:' a commonly used unit of volume measurement in the metric system equal to 10-6 cubic metre, or 1 millilitre. The symbol for cubic centimetre is cm³.',l:''},'cubic foot':{d:'the volume of a cube, all edges of which measure 1 foot. Natural gas is usually measure in cubic feet, with most common standard cubic metre being measure at 60ºF and 14.65 psi.',l:''},'cubic metre':{d:'a unit of volume measurement in the metric system, replacing the previous standard unit known as the barrel, which was equivalent to 35 imperial gallons or 42 United States gallons. The cubic foot metre equals approximately 6.2898 barrels.',l:''},'current method':{d:'also called circulate-and weight method. See circulate-and-weight method.',l:''},'cut drilling fluid':{d:'well control fluid which has been reduced in density or unit weight as a result of entrainment of less dense formation fluids or air. (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'cuttings':{d:'the fragments of rock dislodged by the bit and brought to the surface in the drilling fluid',l:''},'CV ':{d:'Check Valve',l:''},'CVR ':{d:'Critical Velocity Reduction',l:''},'CWP ':{d:'Cold Working Pressure',l:''},'cylinder head':{d:'the device used to seal the top of a cylinder. In modern drilling rig engines, it also houses the valves and has exhaust passages. In four-cycle operation, the cylinder head also has intake passages.',l:''},'cylinder liner':{d:'a removable, replaceable sleeve that fits into a cylinder. When the sliding of the piston and rings wears out the liner, it can be replaced without the block having to be replaced.',l:''},'daily drilling report':{d:'a record made each day of the operations on a working drilling rig.',l:''},'Darcy':{d:'an unit of measure of permeability. a porous medium has a permeability of 1 darcy when a pressure of 1 atmosphere on a sample and 1 cm long an 1 cm² in cross section will force a liquid of 1-cp. viscosity through the sample at the rate of 1 cm³ per second. The permeability of reservoir rocks is usually so low that it is measured in millidarcy units.',l:''},'dart-type blowout preventer':{d:'an inside preventer that is installed on top of the drill stem when the well is kicking though the drill stem. It is stabbed in the open position and then closed against the pressure. The valve that closes is dart shaped, therefore the name.',l:''},'date of manufacture ':{d:'the date of manufacturer’s final acceptance of finished equipment. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'DCS ':{d:'Depth Correlation sub – available in wireline and CT versions',l:''},'DCSSV ':{d:'Direct Controlled Subsurface Safety Valve (also known as DCSSSV)',l:''},'DCV ':{d:'Downhole Control Valves (Advanced Flow Controls)',l:''},'DDV ':{d:'Downhole Deployment Valve',l:''},'de-foamer':{d:'any chemical that prevents or lessens frothing or foaming in another agent.',l:''},'de-sander':{d:'a centrifugal device for removing sand from drilling fluid to prevent abrasion of the pumps. It may be operated mechanically or by a fast-moving stream of fluid inside a special cone shaped vessel, in which case it is sometimes called a hydro-cyclone.',l:''},'de-silter':{d:'a centrifugal device for removing very fine particles, or silt, from drilling fluid to keep the amounts of solids in the fluid at the lowest possible point. Usually, the lower the solids content of fluid, the faster is the rate of penetration. The de-silter works on the same principle as a de-sander.',l:''},'dead well':{d:'1. a well that has ceased to produce oil or gas, either temporarily or permanently. 2. a well that has kicked and has been killed.',l:''},'degasser':{d:'the device used to remove unwanted gas from a liquid, especially from drilling fluid.',l:''},'degree API':{d:'a unit of measurement of the American Petroleum Institute that indicates the weight, or density, of oil. See API gravity.',l:''},'dehydrate':{d:'to remove water from a substance. Dehydration of crude oil is normally accomplished by emulsion treating with emulsion breakers. The water vapour in natural gas must be removed to meet pipeline requirements, a typical maximum allowable water vapour content is 7 lb per MMcf.',l:''},'density':{d:'the mass or weight of a substance per unit volume',l:''},'depth':{d:'1. the distance to which the well is drilled, stipulated in a drilling contract as contract depth. Total depth is the depth after drilling is finished. 2. on offshore drilling rigs, the distance from the baseline of a rig or a ship to the uppermost continuous deck. 3. the maximum pressure that a diver attains during a dive, expressed in feet (metres) of sea water.',l:''},'development well':{d:'a well drilled to permit more effective extraction of oil from a reservoir. Also called an exploitation well.',l:''},'deviation':{d:'the inclination of the wellbore from the vertical. The angle of deviation, angle of drift, or drift angle is the angle in degrees that shows the variation from the vertical as revealed by a deviation survey',l:''},'DH ':{d:'Down Hole',l:''},'diameter':{d:'the distance across a circle, measured through its centre. In the measurement of pipe diameters, the inside diameter is that of the interior circle and the outside diameter that of the exterior circle.',l:''},'differential':{d:'the difference in quantity or degree between two measurement of units. For example, the pressure differential across a choke is the variation between the pressure on one side to that on the other.',l:''},'differential pressure':{d:'the difference between two fluid pressures, for example, the difference between the pressure in a reservoir and in a well bore drilled in the reservoir, or between atmospheric pressure at sea level and at 10.000 feet. also called pressure differential.',l:''},'dip angle':{d:'the maximum angle that the formation makes with the horizontal plane',l:''},'dip azimuth':{d:'the azimuth of the maximum dip or slope of the formation. Also called dip direction.',l:''},'directional drilling':{d:'intentional deviation of a wellbore from vertical',l:''},'DIS ':{d:'Drilling \u0026 Intervention Systems (no longer used as division name)',l:''},'discretization':{d:'Process of breaking down a tool into sub-components. This is often necessary due to diameter changes along the length of a drillstring part.',l:''},'displaced fluid':{d:'a record of the amount of fluid used to push a cement slurry out of the casing string and into the annulus',l:''},'displacement':{d:'the weight of a fluid, such as water, displaced by a freely floating or submerged body (such as an offshore drilling rig). If the body floats, the displacement equals the weight of the body',l:''},'disposal well':{d:'a well through which water is returned to subsurface formations',l:''},'diverter':{d:'a system used to control well blowouts encountered at relatively shallow depths and to protect floating rigs during blowouts encountered at relatively shallow depths and to protect floating rigs during blowouts by directing the flow away from the rig. Diverters differ from Blowout Preventers in that flow is not stopped, but rather the flow is redirected away from the rig.',l:''},'diverter control system':{d:'the assemblage of pumps, accumulators, manifolds, control panels, valves, lines etc., used to operate the diverter system. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'diverter housing':{d:'a permanent installation under the rotary table which houses the diverter unit. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'diverter packer':{d:'refer to Annular Sealing Device',l:''},'diverter panel':{d:'a panel that is dedicated to the diverter and flow line system functions. It is positioned for easy Driller’s access and visual observation of the activated functions.',l:''},'diverter piping':{d:'refer to Vent Line',l:''},'diverter unit':{d:'the device that embodies the annular sealing device and its actuating means. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'DMT ':{d:'Downhole Monitoring Tool',l:''},'dN':{d:'Deca Newtons',l:''},'doghouse':{d:'1. a small enclosure on the rig floor, used as office for the Driller or as a storehouse for small objects. 2. any small building used as an office, a change house, or a place for storage.',l:''},'dogleg':{d:'a short change of direction in the wellbore, frequently resulting in the formation of a key seat',l:''},'dome':{d:'a geological structure resembling an inverted bowl, a short anticline that plunges on all sides.',l:''},'down-hole fluid motor':{d:'also called a turbo-drill or Dyna–Drill. See turbo-drill and Dyna-Drill.',l:''},'downtime':{d:'time during which rig operations are temporarily suspended because of repairs or maintenance.',l:''},'DP ':{d:'drill pipe, used in drilling reports.',l:''},'Drake well':{d:'the first US well drilled in search of oil. Some 69 feet deep, it was drilled near Titusville, PA., and completed in 1859.',l:''},'drill':{d:'to bore a hole in the earth, usually to find and remove subsurface formation fluids such as oil and gas.',l:''},'drill ahead':{d:'to continue drilling operations.',l:''},'drill barge':{d:'a barge, usually towed by a boat, with a complete drilling rig and a submersible hull that is flooded with water at the drilling site.',l:''},'drill bit':{d:'the cutting or boring element used for drilling',l:''},'drill collar':{d:'a heavy, thick-walled tube, usually steel, used between the drill pipe and the bit in the drill stem to provide a pendulum effect to the drill stem and weight to the bit.',l:''},'drill collar sub':{d:'a sub used between the drill string and the drill collars.',l:''},'drill floor substructure':{d:'the foundation structure on which the derrick, rotary table, draw-works and other drilling equipment are supported. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'drill pipe':{d:'heavy seamless tubing in the drill stem that allows fluid to be pumped down the drill stem but prevents flow back up the drill stem, a check valve.',l:''},'drill pipe float':{d:'a valve installed in the drill stem that allows fluid to be pumped down the drill stem but prevents flow back up the drill stem, a check valve.',l:''},'drill pipe pressure':{d:'the amount of pressure exerted inside the drill pipe as a result of circulating pressure, entry of formation pressure into the well, or both.',l:''},'drill pipe pressure gauge':{d:'an indicator, mounted in the fluid circulating system, that measures and indicates the amount of pressure in the drill stem.',l:''},'drill pipe safety valve':{d:'a special valve used to close off the drill pipe to prevent back-flow during a kick. It has threads to match the drill pipe in use.',l:''},'drill ship':{d:'a self-propelled, ocean-going, floating, ship-shaped vessel, equipped with drilling equipment. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'drill stem test (DST)':{d:'the conventional method of formation testing. The basic drill stem test tool consists of a packer or packers, valves or ports that may be opened and closed from the surface, and two or more pressure-recording devices. The tool is lowered on the drill string to the zone to be tested. The packer or packers are set to isolate the zone from the drilling fluid column. The valves or ports are then opened, to allow for formation flow while the recorders chart flow pressures, and are then closed, to shut in the formation while the recorders chart static pressures. A sampling chamber traps clean formation fluids at the end of the test. Analysis of the pressure charts is an important part of formation testing.',l:''},'drill string float':{d:'a check valve in the drill string that will allow fluid to be pumped into the well, but will prevent flow from the well through the drill pipe. (API Recommended Practice 53)',l:''},'drill under pressure':{d:'to carry on drilling operations while maintaining a seal (usually with a rotating head) to prevent the well fluids from blowing out. Drilling under pressure is advantageous in that the rate of penetration is relatively fast, however, the technique requires extreme caution.',l:''},'driller':{d:'the employee directly in charge of a drilling or workover rig and crew. His main duty is operation of the drilling and hoisting equipment, but he is also responsible for down-hole condition of the well operation of down-hole tools, and pipe measurements.',l:''},'driller’s BOP control panel':{d:'also called driller’s console.',l:''},'driller’s method ':{d:'a well-killing method involving two complete and separate circulation’s, the first circulates the kick out of the well and the second circulates heavier fluid through the well bore.',l:''},'driller’s panel':{d:'the BOP control panel mounted at the Drillers position on the rig floor.',l:''},'drilling break':{d:'a sudden increase in the rate of penetration by the drill bit. It sometimes indicates that the bit has penetrated a high-pressure zone and thus warns of the possibility of a blowout.',l:''},'drilling contractor':{d:'an individual or group of individuals that own a drilling rig and contract their services for drilling wells.',l:''},'drilling crew':{d:'a Driller, a Derrickman, and two or more helpers who operate a drilling or workover rig for one tour each day.',l:''},'drilling fluid':{d:'circulating fluid, one function of which is to force cuttings out of the well bore and to the surface. Other functions are to cool the bit and to counteract down hole formation pressure. While a mixture of barite, clay, water and chemical additives is the most common drilling fluid, wells can also be drilled by using air, gas, water, or oil-based fluid as the drilling fluid.',l:''},'drilling fluid additive':{d:'any material added to drilling fluid to change some of its characteristics or properties.',l:''},'drilling fluid balance':{d:'a beam balance consisting of a cup and a graduated arm carrying a sliding weight and resting on a fulcrum, used to determine the density or weight of drilling fluid.',l:''},'drilling fluid cake':{d:'the sheath of fluid solids that forms on the wall of the hole when liquid from fluid filters into the formation; also called wall cake or filter cake.',l:''},'drilling fluid circulation':{d:'the process of pumping fluid downward to the bit and backup to the surface in a drilling or workover operation. See normal circulation and reverse circulation.',l:''},'drilling fluid conditioning':{d:'the treatment and control of drilling fluid to ensure that it has the correct properties. conditioning may include the use of additives, the removal of sand or other solids, the removal of gas, the addition of water, and other measures to prepare the fluid for conditions encountered in s specific well.',l:''},'drilling fluid density':{d:'a measure of the density of a drilling fluid expressed as pounds per gallon (ppg), pounds per cubic foot (lb/ft³), or kilograms per cubic metre (kg/m³). Fluid weight is directly related to the amount of pressure the column of drilling fluid exerts at the bottom of the hole.',l:''},'drilling fluid density recorder':{d:'an instrument in the drilling fluid system which continuously measures drilling fluid density. (API Recommended Practice 53).',l:''},'drilling fluid engineer':{d:'a person whose duty is to test and maintain the properties of the drilling fluid that are specified by the operator.',l:''},'drilling fluid flow indicator':{d:'a device that continually measures and may record the flow rate of fluid returning from the annulus and flowing out of the fluid return line. If the fluid does not flow at a fairly constant rate, a kick or lost circulation may have occurred.',l:''},'drilling fluid flow sensor':{d:'also called fluid-flow indicator.',l:''},'drilling fluid level recorder':{d:'a device that measures and records the height (level) of the drilling fluid in the fluid pits. The level of the fluid in the pits should remain fairly constant during the drilling of a well. If the level rises, however, then the possibility of a kick or a blowout exists. Conversely, if the level falls, then loss of circulation may have occurred. See Pit Level Recorder.',l:''},'drilling fluid logging':{d:'the recording of information derived from examination and analysis of formation cuttings made by the bit and of fluid circulated out of the hole. A portion of the fluid is diverted through a gas-detecting device. Cuttings brought up by the fluid are examined under ultraviolet light detect the presence of oil or gas. Fluid logging is often carried out in a portable laboratory set up at the well.',l:''},'drilling fluid motor':{d:'See Dyna-Drill and turbodrill.',l:''},'drilling fluid pit':{d:'an open pit dug in the ground to hold drilling fluid or waste materials discarded after the treatment of drilling fluid. For some drilling operations, fluid pits are used for suction to the fluid pumps, settling of fluid sediments, and storage of reserve fluid. Steel tanks are much more commonly used for these purposes now, but they are still sometimes referred to as pits.',l:''},'drilling fluid pump':{d:'a large, high-pressure reciprocating pump used to circulate the fluid on drilling rig. A typical fluid pump is a two cylinder, double-acting or three-cylinder, single-acting piston pump whose pistons travel in replaceable liners and are driven by a crankshaft actuated by an engine or motor. Also called a slush pump.',l:''},'drilling fluid return line':{d:'refer to flow line.',l:''},'drilling fluid tank':{d:'one of a series of open tanks, usually made of steel plate, through which the drilling fluid is cycled to allow sand and fine sediments to be removed. Additives are mixed with the fluid in the tanks, and the fluid is temporarily stored there before being pumped back into the well. Modern rotary drilling rigs are generally provided with three or more tanks, fitted with built-in piping, valves, and fluid agitators. Also called fluid pits.',l:''},'drilling spool':{d:'a connection component with ends either flanged or hubbed. it must have an internal diameter at least equal to the bore of the Blowout Preventer and can have smaller side outlets for connecting auxiliary lines. (API Recommended Practice 53).',l:''},'drillpipe pressure':{d:'the amount of pressure exerted inside the drillpipe as a result of circulating pressure, entry of formation pressure into the well, or both',l:''},'drillship':{d:'a self-propelled, oceangoing ship that is equipped with a derrick amidships and all associated drilling equipment.',l:''},'drive pipe':{d:'a relatively short string of large diameter pipe driven or forced into the ground to function as “conductor pipe”. (API Recommended Practice 53).',l:''},'dry hole':{d:'any well that does not produce oil or gas in commercial quantities. A dry hole may flow water, gas or even oil, but not enough to justify production.',l:''},'DSAF ':{d:'Double Studded Adapter Flange',l:''},'DST ':{d:'Drill Stem Testing',l:''},'DTS ':{d:'Distributive Temperature Sensor (as per Weatherford fiber optics)',l:''},'duplex pump':{d:'a reciprocating pump having two pistons or plungers, used extensively as a fluid pump on drilling rigs.',l:''},'DwC ':{d:'Drilling with Casing',l:''},'DWS ':{d:'Drilling \u0026 Well Systems (old WFT division)',l:''},'Dyna-Drill':{d:'a down hole motor driven by drilling fluid that imparts rotary motion to a drilling bit connected to the tool, thus eliminating the need to turn the entire drill stem to make hole. The Dyna-Drill, a trade name, is used in straight and directional drilling.',l:''},'dynamic well kill procedure':{d:'a planned operation to control a flowing well by injecting fluid of a sufficient density and at a sufficient rate into the well bore to effect a kill without completely closing in the well with the surface containing equipment. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'dynamically positioned drilling vessels':{d:'drill-ships and semi-submersible drilling rigs equipped with computer controlled thrusters which enable them to maintain a constant position relative to the sea floor without the use of anchors and mooring lines while conducting floating drilling operations. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'easting':{d:'map coordinate measured eastward from North/South line',l:''},'ECD':{d:'equivalent circulating density',l:''},'ECD vs. flow rate':{d:'a record of the effective density exerted by a circulating fluid against the formation compared to the volume, mass, or weight of a fluid passing through any conductor per unit of time',l:''},'ECV ':{d:'External Casing Valve',l:''},'EDI ':{d:'Evaluation Drilling \u0026 Intervention Systems (from Oct 2005 – formerly DWS)',l:''},'effective permeability':{d:'a measure of the ability of a single fluid through a rock when the pore spaces of the rock are not completely filled or saturated with the fluid.',l:''},'effective porosity':{d:'the percentage of the bulk volume of a rock ample that is composed of inter-connected pore spaces which allow the passage of fluid s through the sample. See porosity.',l:''},'EGP ':{d:'External Gravel Pack',l:''},'EHO ':{d:'Eastern Hemisphere Operations',l:''},'electric line':{d:'single or multiple electrical conductor housed, within a braided wireline. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'electric pump':{d:'an electrically driven hydraulic pump, usually a 3-piston (triplex) pump. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'electro-hydraulic (EH) system':{d:'a control system that uses an electrical signal to actuate a solenoid operated hydraulic valve to hydraulically pilot a control valve to operate a function. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'ELEV (elev) ':{d:'Elevation - Rig floor to zero point on wellhead distance',l:''},'EM ':{d:'Electro Magnetic (as in LWD/MWD transmission signal)',l:''},'EMR ':{d:'Electronic Memory Recorder',l:''},'EMW':{d:'equivalent mud weight',l:''},'end and outlet connections':{d:'integral flanges, studded or open faced, and hub connections used to join together equipment that contains or controls pressure. (API Specification 16A).',l:''},'EOR ':{d:'Enhanced Oil Recovery',l:''},'equipment':{d:'any single completed unit that can be used for its intended purpose without further processing or assembly. (API Specification 16A).',l:''},'equivalent circulating density':{d:'1. the effective density exerted by a circulating fluid against the formation that takes into account the pressure drop in the annulus above the point being considered.\n\n2. the sum of pressure exerted by hydrostatic head of fluid, drilled solids and friction pressure losses in the annulus, divided by the depth of interest and by 0.052, if ECD is to be expressed in pounds per gallon (lbs/gal). (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'ERC ':{d:'Extended Reach Completion',l:''},'ERD ':{d:'Extended Reach Development',l:''},'erosion':{d:'the process by which material (such as rock or soil) is worn away or removed (as by wind or water).',l:''},'ESD ':{d:'Emergency Shut Down',l:''},'ESP ':{d:'Electric Submersible Pump',l:''},'ESS ':{d:'Expandable Sand Screens',l:''},'ETC ':{d:'Expandable Top Connector',l:''},'EU ':{d:'External Upset (on tubing joint)',l:''},'exploitation well':{d:'a well drilled to permit more effective extraction of oil from a reservoir. sometimes called a development well.',l:''},'exploration well':{d:'also called a wildcat.',l:''},'exploratory well':{d:'a well drilled in an unproven area, to find a new reservoir in a field that\u0027s already productive or to extend a known reservoir',l:''},'EZI ':{d:'Expandable Zonal Isolation',l:''},'F ':{d:'Fahrenheit ( oF )',l:''},'Fahrenheit scale':{d:'a temperature scale devised by Gabriel Fahrenheit, in which 32 degrees represents the freezing point and 212 degrees the boiling point of water at standard sea-level pressure. Fahrenheit degrees may be converted to Celsius degrees by using the following formula: C = 5/9 x (F – 32)',l:''},'fault':{d:'a break in subsurface strata. Often strata on one side of the fault line have been displaced (upward, downward, or laterally) relative to their original positions.',l:''},'fault plane':{d:'a surface along which faulting has occurred.',l:''},'fault trap':{d:'a surface hydrocarbon trap created by faulting, which causes an impermeable rock layer to be moved opposite the reservoir bed.',l:''},'FC ':{d:'Flow Coupling',l:''},'FCV ':{d:'Fluid Control Valve',l:''},'feed-in (influx, inflow)':{d:'the flow of fluids from the formation into the well bore. (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'fill the hole':{d:'to pump drilling fluid into the well bore while the pipe is being withdrawn, in order to ensure that the well bore remains full or fluid even though the pipe is withdrawn. Filling the hole lessens the danger of blowout or of caving of the wall of the well bore.',l:''},'fill-up (flood valve)':{d:'a differentially set valve, installed on marine risers that automatically permits sea water to enter the riser to prevent collapse under hydrostatic pressure after evacuation caused by lost circulation or by gas circulated into the riser. (API Recommended Practice 53).',l:''},'filter cake':{d:'1. compacted solid or semisolid material remaining on a filter after pressure filtration of fluid with a standard filter press. Thickness of the cake is reported in thirty-seconds of an inch or in millimetres. 2. the layer of concentrated solids from the drilling fluid or cement slurry that forms on the walls of the borehole opposite permeable formations, also called wall cake or fluid cake.',l:''},'filter loss':{d:'the amount of fluid that can be delivered through a permeable filter medium after being subjected to a set differential pressure for a set length of time.',l:''},'final circulating pressure':{d:'drill pressure required to circulate at the selected kill rate adjusted for increase in kill drilling fluid density over the original drilling fluid density. Used from the time kill drilling fluid reaches the bottom of the drill string until kill operations are completed, or a change in either kill drilling fluid density or kill rate is effected. (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'fish':{d:'an object that is left in the well bore during drilling or workover operations and that must be recovered before work can proceed. It can be anything from a piece of scrap metal to a part of the drill stem. v: 1. to recover from a well any equipment left there during drilling operations, such as a lost bit or drill collar or part of the drill string. 2. to remove from an older well certain pieces of equipment (such as packers, liners, or screen pipe) to allow reconditioning of the well.',l:''},'fishing diagram':{d:'A depiction of the geometry of all the parts and tools in the drillstring.',l:''},'fixed choke':{d:'a choke, whose opening is one size only, its opening is not adjustable.',l:''},'flammable liquid':{d:'any liquid having a flash point of 100(F (37.78(C) or less. these liquids are easily ignited. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'flange':{d:'a projecting rim or edge (as on pipe fittings and openings in pumps and vessels) usually drilled with holes and having a sealing mechanism, used to join pressure containing equipment by bolting to other flanged fittings. (API Specification 16A).',l:''},'flange, blind':{d:'a flange with no centre bore, used to close off completely a flanged end or outlet connection. (API Specification 16A).',l:''},'flare':{d:'an arrangement of piping and burners used to dispose (by burning) of surplus combustible vapours, usually situated near a gasoline plant, refinery, or producing well. v: to dispose of surplus combustible vapours by igniting them in the atmosphere. Currently, flaring is rarely used because of the high value of gas as well as the stringent air pollution controls.',l:''},'flash point':{d:'the minimum temperature at which a product momentarily ignites, but does not burn continuously. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'flex/ball joint':{d:'a device installed directly above the subsea Blowout Preventer stack and at the top of the telescopic riser joint to permit relative angular movement of the riser to reduce stresses due to vessel motions and environmental forces.',l:''},'float':{d:'an element of a level-control assembly designed to operate while partially or completely submerged in a liquid, the level of which is controlled by the assembly. the buoyancy of the liquid activates the float and the control valve to which it is linked and modifies the rate of the inflow or the outflow of the vessel to maintain a pre-set level. Sometimes a drill pipe float is called simply a float.',l:''},'float valve':{d:'a drill pipe float.',l:''},'flow coupling':{d:'a heavy walled nipple or fitting designed to resist erosion that can result from turbulence created by a restriction in the flow string. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'flow line':{d:'the piping which exits the bell nipple and conducts drilling fluid and cuttings to the shale shaker and drilling fluid pits. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'flow line sensor':{d:'a device to monitor rate of fluid flow from the annulus. (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'flow line valve':{d:'a valve which controls the flow of drilling fluid through the flow line. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'fluid density':{d:'the unit weight of fluid, e.g. pounds per gallon (lbs/gal). (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'fluid level vs. bit depth':{d:'a record of the depth or distance from surface that the fluid in a well incapable of natural flow will reach under static conditions',l:''},'FMIT ':{d:'Fiber in Metal Tube',l:''},'FMS':{d:'Field Monitoring Station',l:''},'FO ':{d:'Fiber Optic',l:''},'forging':{d:'n: plastically deforming metal, usually hot, into desired shapes with compressive force, with open or closed dies. n: a shaped metal part formed by the forging method. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'FORJ ':{d:'Fiber Optic Rotary Joint',l:''},'formation':{d:'a bed or deposit composed throughout of substantially the same kind of rock, a lithologic unit. Each different formation is given a name, frequently as a result of the study of the formation outcrop at surface and sometimes based on fossils found in the formation.',l:''},'formation breakdown':{d:'an event occurring when borehole pressure is a magnitude that the exposed formation accepts whole fluid from the borehole. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'formation competency test (formation integrity test)':{d:'application of pressure by superimposing a surface pressure on a fluid column in order to determine ability of a subsurface zone to withstand a certain hydrostatic pressure. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'formation factor':{d:'A coefficient that accounts for formation strength and the cutting aggressiveness of the bit.',l:''},'formation fluid':{d:'fluid (such as gas, oil or water) that exists in a subsurface rock formation.',l:''},'formation fracture gradient':{d:'the hydrostatic value expressed in psi./ft that is required to initiate a fracture in subsurface formation. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'formation pressure':{d:'the force exerted by fluids in a formation, recorded in the hole at the level of the formation with the well shut in. Also called reservoir pressure or shut-in bottom-hole pressure.',l:''},'formation type':{d:'a description of the material that composes a particular section of the formation.',l:''},'formation water':{d:'the water originally in place in a formation.',l:''},'FP ':{d:'Formation Pressure',l:''},'FPSU ':{d:'Floating Production and Storage Unit',l:''},'fracture gradient':{d:'the pressure gradient at which the formation accepts whole fluid from the well bore.',l:''},'FSU ':{d:'Floating Storage Unit',l:''},'FSV ':{d:'Formation Saver Valve',l:''},'ft':{d:'foot',l:''},'ft-lb':{d:'foot-pound',l:''},'ft/min':{d:'feet per minute.',l:''},'ft/s':{d:'feet per second.',l:''},'FTP (FTHP) ':{d:'Flowing Tubing (Head) Pressure',l:''},'ft²':{d:'square foot',l:''},'ft³':{d:'cubic foot',l:''},'ft³/bbl':{d:'cubic feet per barrel.',l:''},'ft³/d':{d:'cubic feet per day.',l:''},'ft³/min':{d:'cubic feet per minute',l:''},'ft³/s':{d:'cubic feet per second.',l:''},'function':{d:'operation of a BOP, choke or kill valve or other component, in one direction (example, closing the blind rams is a function, opening the blind rams is a separate function). (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'gal':{d:'gallon',l:''},'gallon':{d:'a unit of measure of liquid capacity that equals 3.785 litres and has a volume of 231 in³. A gallon of water weighs 8.34 lb at 60ºF. T he imperial gallon, used in Great Britain, is equal to approximately 1.2 U.S. gallons.',l:''},'gas':{d:'a compressible fluid that completely fills any container in which it is confined. Technically, a gas will not condense when it is compressed and cooled, because a gas can exist only above the critical temperature for its particular composition. Below the critical temperature, this form of matter is known as a vapour, because liquid can exist and condensation can occur. Sometimes the terms gas and vapour are used interchangeably. However, the term vapour should be only used for those streams in which condensation can occur and which originate from or are in equilibrium with, a liquid phase.',l:''},'gas buster':{d:'a slang term to denote a mud-gas separator.',l:''},'gas constant':{d:'a constant number, mathematically the product of the total volume and the total pressure divided by the absolute temperature for 1 mole of any ideal gas or mixture of ideal gases at any temperature.',l:''},'gas drilling':{d:'See air drilling.',l:''},'gas reservoir':{d:'a geological formation containing a single gaseous phase. when produced, the surface equipment may or may not contain condensed liquid, depending on the temperature, pressure and composition of the single reservoir phase.',l:''},'gas-cut fluid':{d:'a drilling fluid that has entrained formation gas giving the fluid a characteristically fluffy texture. When entrained gas is not released before the fluid returns to the well, the weight or density of the fluid column. Because a large amount of gas in fluid lowers its density, gas cut fluid must be treated to reduce the change of a blowout.',l:''},'gate valve':{d:'a valve which employs a sliding gate to open or close the flow passage. The valve may or may not be full-opening.',l:''},'gauge pressure':{d:'the amount of pressure exerted on the interior walls of a vessel by the fluid contained in it (as indicated by a pressure gauge), it is expressed in psig (pounds per square inch gauge) or in kilopascals. Gauge pressure plus atmospheric pressure equals absolute pressure. See absolute pressure.',l:''},'GBU ':{d:'Global Business Unit',l:''},'GC ':{d:'Gauge Cutter',l:''},'gel':{d:'n: a semisolid. jelly like state assumed by some colloidal dispersions at rest. When agitated, the gel converts to a fluid state. Also a nickname for bentonite. v: to take the from of a gel, to set.',l:''},'gel strength':{d:'a measure of the ability of a colloidal dispersion to develop and retain a gel form, based on its resistance to shear. The gel strength, or shear strength of a drilling fluid determines its ability to hold solids in suspension. Sometimes bentonite and other colloidal clays are added to drilling fluid to increase its gel strength.',l:''},'GLM ':{d:'Gas Lift Mandrel',l:''},'GLV ':{d:'Gas Lift Valve',l:''},'glycol':{d:'a group of compounds used to dehydrate gaseous or liquid hydrocarbons or to inhibit the formation of hydrates. Commonly used glycol’s are ethylene glycol, diethylene glycol, and triethylene glycol.',l:''},'go in the hole':{d:'to lower the drill stem into the well bore.',l:''},'GoM ':{d:'Gulf of Mexico',l:''},'GP ':{d:'Gravel Pack (also WFT Product Line) Refer HUN also',l:''},'gpm':{d:'gallons per minute',l:''},'graben':{d:'a block of the earth’s crust that has slid downward between two faults, the opposite of a horst.',l:''},'gunk plug':{d:'a volume of gunk slurry placed in the well bore. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'gunk squeeze':{d:'procedure whereby a gunk slurry is pumped into a subsurface zone. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'gunk-slurry':{d:'a slang term to denote a mixture of diesel oil and bentonite. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'H2S':{d:'hydrogen sulphide.',l:''},'hanger plug':{d:'a device placed or hung in the casing below the Blowout Preventer stack to form a pressure-tight seal. Pressure is then applied to the Blowout Preventer stack in order to test it for leaks.',l:''},'hard shut-in':{d:'to close in a well by closing a Blowout Preventer with the choke and/or choke line valve closed. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'hazardous substance':{d:'a substance which by reason of being explosive, flammable, toxic, corrosive, oxidising, irritating or otherwise harmful, has the potential to cause injury, illness or death. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'HCAU ':{d:'Hydraulic Control Actuating Unit (now HCAU-3)',l:''},'HCS ':{d:'Hydril CS',l:''},'head':{d:'1. the height of a column of liquid required to produce a specific pressure. See hydraulic head. 2. for centrifugal pumps, the velocity of flowing fluid converted into pressure expressed in feet or metres of flowing fluid. Also called velocity head. 3. That part of a machine (such as a pump or an engine) that is one the end of the cylinder opposite the crankshaft.',l:''},'heat (cast lot)':{d:'material originating from a final melt. For re-melted alloys, a heat shall be defined as the raw material originating from a single re-melted ingot. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'heat affected zone (HAZ)':{d:'that portion of the base metal which has not been melted, but whose mechanical properties or microstructure has been altered by the heat of welding or cutting. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'heat treatment (heat treating)':{d:'alternate steps of controlled heating and cooling of materials for the purpose of changing physical or mechanical properties. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'heat treatment load':{d:'that material placed on loading or carrying devices moved as a batch through one heat treatment cycles. (API Specification 16A).',l:''},'heave':{d:'the vertical motion of a ship or a floating offshore drilling rig.',l:''},'heave compensator':{d:'a device that moves with the heave of a floating offshore drilling rig to prevent the bit from being lifted off the bottom of the hole and then dropped back down (i.e., to maintain constant weight on the bit). It is used with devices such as bumper subs. See motion compensator.',l:''},'heavyweight drill pipe':{d:'drill pipe having thicker walls and longer tool joints than usual and also an integral wear pad in the middle. Several joints of this pipe may be placed in the drill stem between drill collars and regular drill pipe to reduce the chances of drill pipe fatigue or failure. (Also known as heavy wall drill pipe.)',l:''},'heel':{d:'the inclination of a ship or a floating offshore drilling rig to one side, caused by wind, waves, or shifting weights on board.',l:''},'HEL':{d:'Hostile Environment Logging',l:''},'HFC ':{d:'Hydraulic Flow Controls',l:''},'HGP ':{d:'Hydraulic Gas Pump',l:''},'high-pressure squeeze cementing':{d:'the forcing of cement slurry into a well at the points to be sealed with a final pressure equal to or greater than the formation breakdown pressure. See squeeze cementing.',l:''},'hole':{d:'1. in drilling operations, the well bore or borehole. See well bore and borehole. 2. an opening that us made purposely or accidentally in any solid substance.',l:''},'hole opener':{d:'a device used to enlarge the size of an existing borehole, having teeth arranged on its outside circumference to cut the formation as it rotates.',l:''},'hook':{d:'a large, hook-shaped device from which the swivel is suspended. It is designed to carry maximum loads ranging from 100 to 650 tons (90 to 590 tonnes) and turns on bearings in its supporting housing. A strong spring within the assembly cushions the weight of a stand (90 feet or about 27 metres) of drill pipe, thus permitting the pipe to be made up and broken out with less damage to the tool joint threads. Smaller hooks without the spring are used for handling tubing and sucker rods.',l:''},'hookload':{d:'total force pulling down on the hook. This total force includes the weight of the drillstring in air, the drill collars and any ancillary equipment, reduced by any force that tends to reduce that weight. Some forces that might reduce the weight include friction along the wellbore wall (especially in deviated wells) and, importantly, buoyant forces on the drillstring caused by its immersion in drilling fluid.',l:''},'hopper':{d:'a large funnel or cone-shaped device into which dry components (such as powdered clay or cement) can be poured in order to uniformly mix the components with water or other liquids. the liquid is injected through a nozzle at the bottom of the hopper. The resulting mixture of dry material and liquid may be drilling fluid to be used as the circulating fluid in a rotary drilling operation, or it may be cement slurry to be used in bonding casing to the borehole.',l:''},'horsepower':{d:'a unit of measure of work done by a machine. One horsepower equals 33.000 foot-pounds per minute.',l:''},'horst':{d:'a block of the earth’s crust that has been raised up between two faults, the opposite of a graben.',l:''},'hose bundle':{d:'see control hose bundle.',l:''},'hot working':{d:'deforming metal plastically at such a temperature and rate that hardness and strength do not increase.',l:''},'hp':{d:'horsepower',l:''},'hp-h':{d:'horsepower-hour',l:''},'HPHT ':{d:'High Pressure High Temperature',l:''},'HPNS':{d:'high-pressure nervous syndrome.',l:''},'HPS ':{d:'Hydraulic Pump System',l:''},'HPU ':{d:'Hydraulic Power Unit',l:''},'HSP ':{d:'Hydrostatic Pressure',l:''},'HT ':{d:'High Temperature',l:''},'HUD ':{d:'Hang (Hold) Up Depth - For clean tubing ID',l:''},'hull':{d:'the framework of a vessel including all decks, plating, and columns, but excluding machinery.',l:''},'HUN ':{d:'Hook up Nipple (Gravel Pack option)',l:''},'HWDP':{d:'heavyweight drillpipe',l:''},'HWO ':{d:'Hydraulic Workover Unit (Snubbing Unit)',l:''},'Hydrafrac':{d:'the copyrighted name of a method of hydraulic fracturing for increasing productivity.',l:''},'hydrate':{d:'n: a hydrocarbon and water compound that is formed under reduced temperature and pressure in gathering, compression, and transmission facilities for gas. Hydrates often accumulate in troublesome snow or ice. v: to enlarge by taking water on or in.',l:''},'hydration':{d:'reaction of cement with water. The powdered cement gradually sets to a solid as hydration continues.',l:''},'hydraulic connector':{d:'a mechanical connector that is activated hydraulically and connects the BOP stack to the well-head or the LMRP to the BOP stack. See Lower marine Riser Package. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'hydraulic control pod':{d:'a device used on offshore drilling rigs to provide a way to actuate and control subsea Blowout Preventers from the rig. Hydraulic lines from the rig enter the pods, through which fluid is sent toward the preventer. Usually two pods, painted different colours, are used, each to safeguard and back up the other.',l:''},'hydraulic fluid':{d:'a liquid of low viscosity (such as light oil) that is used in systems actuated by liquid (such as the brake system in a modern passenger car.)',l:''},'hydraulic fracturing':{d:'an operation in which a specially blended liquid is pumped down a well and into a formation under pressure high enough to cause the formation to crack open. The resulting cracks or fractures serve as passages through which oil can flow into the well bore.',l:''},'hydraulic head':{d:'the force exerted by a column of liquid expressed by the height of the liquid above the point at which the pressure is measured. Although head refers to distance or height, it is used to express pressure, since the force of the liquid column is directly proportional to its height. Also called head or hydrostatic head',l:''},'hydraulics':{d:'the branch of science that deals with practical applications of water or other liquid in motion.',l:''},'hydraulics power vs. flow rate':{d:'a record of the energy per unit of time that is being expended across the bit nozzles compared to the volume, mass, or weight of a fluid passing through any conductor per unit of time',l:''},'Hydril':{d:'the registered trademark of a prominent manufacturer of oil field equipment, especially the annular Blowout Preventer.',l:''},'hydrocarbons':{d:'organic compounds of hydrogen and carbon, whose densities, boiling points, and freezing points increase as their molecular weights increase. Although composed of only two elements, hydrocarbons exist in a variety of compounds because of the strong affinity of the carbon atom for other atoms and for itself. The smallest molecules of hydrocarbons are gaseous, the largest are solids. Petroleum is a mixture of many different hydrocarbons. hydrochloric acid',l:''},'hydrochloric acid':{d:'an acid compound commonly used to acidize carbonate rocks, prepared by mixing hydrogen chloride gas in water. Also known as muriatic acid. its chemical formula is HCl.',l:''},'hydrocyclone':{d:'a cone-shaped separator for separating various sizes of particles and liquid by centrifugal force. See desander and desilter.',l:''},'hydrodynamic brake':{d:'a device mounted on the end of the draw-works shaft of a drilling rig. The hydrodynamic brake serves as an auxiliary to the mechanical brake when pipe is lowered into the well. The braking effect of a hydrodynamic brake is achieved by means of an impeller turning in a housing filled with water. Sometimes called hydraulic brake or Hydromatic (a manufacturer’s term) brake.',l:''},'hydrogen sulphide (H2S)':{d:'a flammable, colourless gaseous compound of hydrogen and sulphur (H2S) with the odour of rotten eggs. Commonly found in petroleum, it causes the foul smell of petroleum fractions. It is extremely corrosive and poisonous, causing damage to skin, eyes, breathing passages, and lungs and attacking and paralysing the nervous system, particularly that part controlling the lungs and heart. Also called hepatic gas or sulphured hydrogen.',l:''},'hydrogen sulphide service':{d:'refers to equipment designed to resist corrosion and hydrogen embattlement caused by exposure to hydrogen sulphide. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'hydrophone':{d:'an underwater listening device that converts acoustic energy to electrical signals. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'hydrostatic head':{d:'the true vertical length of fluid column, normally in feet. (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'hydrostatic pressure':{d:'the force exerted by a body of fluid at rest, it increases directly with the density and depth of the fluid and is expressed in psi or kPa. The hydrostatic pressure of fresh water is 0.433 psi per foot of depth (9.792 kPa/m). In drilling, the term refers to the pressure exerted by the drilling fluid in the well bore. In a water-drive field, the term refers to the pressure that may furnish the primary energy for production.',l:''},'IADC':{d:'International Association of Drilling Contractors, formerly the American Association of Oilwell Drilling Contractors (AAODC).',l:''},'ICD ':{d:'International Contract Drilling (formerly part of Precision )',l:''},'ICT ':{d:'Intelligent Completion Technology (aka IWT – Intelligent Well Technology)',l:''},'ID':{d:'inside diameter',l:''},'idle':{d:'to operate an engine without applying a load to it.',l:''},'IFR':{d:'In-Field Reference',l:''},'igneous rock':{d:'a rock mass formed by the solidification of material poured (when molten) into the earth’s crust or onto its surface. Granite is an igneous rock.',l:''},'IGP ':{d:'Internal Gravel Pack',l:''},'ILS ':{d:'International Lift Systems',l:''},'impending blowout':{d:'early manifestation or indication of a blowout.',l:''},'impermeable':{d:'preventing the passage of fluid. a formation may be porous yet impermeable if there is an absence of connecting passages between the voids within it. See permeability.',l:''},'impression block':{d:'a block with lead or another relatively soft material on its bottom. It is made up on drill pipe or tubing at the surface, fun into a well, and allowed to set on a tool or other object that has been lost in the well. When the block is retrieved the size, shape, and position of the fish are obtained from the examination of the impression left in the lead, and an appropriate fishing tool may be selected.',l:''},'in.':{d:'square inch.',l:''},'Inc':{d:'inclination',l:''},'inclination':{d:'wellbore deviation from vertical at a specified MD',l:''},'indicated volume':{d:'the change in meter reading that occurs during a receipt or delivery of a liquid product.',l:''},'inert gas':{d:'the part of a breathing medium that serves as a transport for oxygen and is not used by the body as a life-support agent. Its purpose is to dilute the flow of oxygen to the lungs, thereby preventing oxygen toxicity.',l:''},'inflow':{d:'see Feed-in',l:''},'inhibitor':{d:'an additive used to retard undesirable chemical action in a product, added in small quantity to gasolines to prevent oxidation and gum formation, to lubricating oils to stop the colour change, and to corrosive environments to decrease corrosive action.',l:''},'initial circulating pressure':{d:'drill pipe pressure required to circulate initially at the selected kill rate while holding casing pressure at the closed-in value, numerically equal to kill rate circulating pressure, plus closed-in drill pipe pressure. (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'injection':{d:'the process of forcing fluid into something. In a diesel engine, the introduction of high-pressure fuel oil into the cylinders.',l:''},'injection well':{d:'a well used for injection fluids into an underground stratum to increase reservoir pressure',l:''},'inland barge':{d:'a drill barge that is submerged to rest on the bottom. Inland barges are typically used to drill wells in shallow water, such as marshes and inland bays.',l:''},'inland barge rig':{d:'a drilling structure consisting of a barge upon which the drilling equipment is constructed. When moved from one location to another, the barge floats, but, when stationed on the drill site, the barge is submerged to rest on the bottom. Typically, inland barge rigs are used to drill wells in marshes, shallow inland bays, and areas where the water covering the drill site is not too deep.',l:''},'inner barrel':{d:'the part of a telescopic slip joint on a marine riser which is attached to the flexible joint beneath the diverter.',l:''},'insert type packer':{d:'a diverter element which uses inserts designed to close and seal on specific ranges of pipe diameter. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'inside blowout preventer':{d:'a valve installed in the drill stem to prevent a blowout through the stem. Also called an internal Blowout Preventer.',l:''},'instrumentation':{d:'a device or assembly of devices designed for one or more of the following functions: to measure operating variables (such as pressure, temperature, rate of flow, speed of rotation, etc) to indicate these phenomena with visible or audible signals, to record them, to control them within a predetermined range, and to stop operations if the control fails. Simple instrumentation might consist of an indicating pressure gauge only. In a completely automatic system, desired ranges of pressure, temperature, and so on are predetermined and preset.',l:''},'integral valve':{d:'a valve embodied in the diverter unit which operates integrally with the annular sealing device. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'interlock':{d:'an arrangement of control system functions designed to require the actuation of one function as a prerequisite to actuate another. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'intermediate casing string':{d:'the string of casing set in a well after the surface casing is set to keep the hole from caving and to seal off troublesome formations. The string is sometimes called protection casing.',l:''},'internal blowout preventer':{d:'also called inside Blowout Preventer. See inside blowout preventer.',l:''},'internal upset':{d:'an extra-thick wall on one end of tubing or drill pipe at the point where it is threaded to compensate for the metal removed in threading. Unlike conventional drill pipe, which has the extra thickness on the outside, drill pipe with internal upset has the extra thickness inside and a uniform, straight wall outside.',l:''},'internal-upset pipe':{d:'tubular goods in which the pipe walls at the threaded end are thickened (upset) on the inside to provide extra strength in the tool joints. Thus the outer wall of the pipe is the same diameter throughout its length. Upset casing is normally run at the top of long strings in deep operations.',l:''},'international system of units':{d:'a system of units measurement based on the metric system, adopted and described by the Eleventh General Conference of Weights and measures. It provides an international standard of measurement to be followed when certain customary units, both API (Field Units) and metric, are eventually phased out of international trade operations. The symbol SI (le Systeme International d’Unites) designates the system, which involves seven base units. 1. metre for length, 2. kilogram for mass, 3. second for time, 4. Kelvin for temperature, 5. ampere for electric current, 6. candela for luminous intensity, and 7. mole for amount of substance. From these units others are derived without introducing numerical factors.',l:''},'interval':{d:'a designated portion of a zone. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'Interval 0':{d:'a special interval used to account for the distance between the rig floor and the top of the formation',l:''},'intrusive rock':{d:'an igneous rock that, while molten, penetrated into or between other rocks and solidified.',l:''},'invaded zone':{d:'an area within a permeable rock adjacent to a well bore into which a filtrate (usually water) from the drilling fluid has passed, with consequent partial or total displacement of the fluids originally present in the zone.',l:''},'IPP ':{d:'Injection Production Packer (Inflatable Packer product line)',l:''},'IPS ':{d:'Improved Plow Steel',l:''},'iron roughneck':{d:'manufacturer’s term for a floor-mounted combination of a spinning wrench and a torque wrench. The iron roughneck moves into a position hydraulically and eliminates the manual handling involved with suspended individual tools.',l:''},'iron sponge process':{d:'a method of removing small concentrations of hydrogen sulphide from natural gas by passing the gas over a bed of wood shavings which have been impregnated with a form of iron oxide. The impregnated wood shavings are called iron sponge. The hydrogen sulphide reacts with the iron oxide, forming iron sulphide and water.',l:''},'isogonic chart':{d:'a map that shows the isogonic lines joining point of magnetic declination, which is the variation between magnetic north and true north. For example, in Los Angeles, California, when the compass needle is pointing toward north, true north actually lies 15° east of magnetic north.',l:''},'isogonic line':{d:'an imaginary line on a map that joins places on the earth’s surface at which the variation of a magnetic compass needle from true north is the same. This variation, which may range from 0 to 30 or more degrees either east or west of true north, must be compensated for to obtain an accurate reading of direction.',l:''},'ISP ':{d:'Inflatable Straddle Packer (Inflatable Packer product line)',l:''},'ITCP ':{d:'Integral (Integrated) Tubing Conveyed Perforator',l:''},'IWCF':{d:'the International Well Control Forum, established on 1 January 1993, is an industry membership organisation whose function is to provide an international competency assessment standard for personnel involved in well operations.',l:''},'IWT ':{d:'Intelligent Well Technology (aka ICT - Intelligent Completion Technology)',l:''},'jack-up drilling rig':{d:'an offshore structure with tubular or derrick legs that support the deck and hull. When positioned over the drilling site, the bottoms of the legs rest on the sea floor. A jack-up rig is towed or propelled to a location with its leg up. Once the legs are firmly positioned on the bottom, the deck and hull height are adjusted and levelled.',l:''},'jacket':{d:'tubular piece of steel in a tubing-liner type of sucker rod pump, inside of which is placed an accurately bored and honed liner. In this type of sucker rod pump, the pump plunger moves up and down within the liner, and liner is inside the jacket.',l:''},'jackup rig':{d:'an offshore rig with legs that support the deck and rest on the sea floor at the drill site',l:''},'jar':{d:'a percussion tool operated mechanically or hydraulically to deliver a heavy hammer blow to objects in the borehole. Jars are used to free objects.',l:''},'jar accelerator':{d:'a hydraulic tool used in conjunction with a jar and made up on the fishing string above the jar to increase the power of the hammer blow.',l:''},'jet':{d:'1. a hydraulic device operated by pump pressure to clean fluid pits and tanks in rotary drilling and to mix fluid components. 2. in a perforating gun using shaped charges, a highly penetrating, fast moving stream of exploded particles that cuts a hole in the casing, cement, and formation.',l:''},'jet bit':{d:'a drilling bit having replaceable nozzles through which the drilling fluid is directed in a velocity stream to the bottom of the hole to improve the efficiency of the bit. See bit.',l:''},'jet impact force vs. flow rate':{d:'a record of the amount of force produced by the jet compared to the  volume, mass, or weight of a fluid passing through any nozzle per unit of time',l:''},'joint':{d:'a single length (30 feet or 9m) of drill pipe, drill collar, casing, or tubing that has threaded connections at both ends. Several joints screwed together constitute a stand of pipe.',l:''},'joule':{d:'the unit used to measure heat, work and energy in the metric system. Its symbol is J. It is the amount of energy required to move an object of 1 kilogram mass to a height of 1 metre. Also called a Newton-metre.',l:''},'Joule-Thomson effect':{d:'the change in gas temperature which occurs when the gas is expanded adiabatically from a higher pressure to a lower pressure. The effect for most gases, except hydrogen and helium, is a cooling of the gas.',l:''},'junk':{d:'n: metal debris lost in a hole. Junk may be a lost bit, pieces of a bit, milled pieces of pipe, wrenches , or any relatively small object that impedes drilling and must be fished out of the hole. v: to abandon (as a non-productive well).',l:''},'junk basket':{d:'a device made up on the bottom of the drill stem to catch pieces of junk from the bottom of the hole. Fluid circulation forces the junk into a barrel in the tool, where it is held by metal projections, or catchers. When the basket is brought back to the surface, the junk is removed. Also called a junk sub.',l:''},'junk sub':{d:'also called a junk basket. See junk basket.',l:''},'k ':{d:'Designation for 1000’s eg: 5k psi = 5,000 psi',l:''},'KB ':{d:'Kelly Bushing – rig floor zero point',l:''},'Kelly':{d:'the heavy steel member, three-, four-, six-, or eight-sided, suspended from the swivel through the rotary table and connected to the topmost joint of drill pipe to turn the drill stem as the rotary table turns. It has a bored passageway that permits fluid to be circulated into the drill stem and up the annulus, or vice versa.',l:''},'Kelly bushing':{d:'a special device that, when fitted into the master bushing, transmits torque to the Kelly and simultaneously permits vertical movement of the Kelly to make hole. It may be shaped to fit the rotary opening or have pins for transmitting torque. Also called the drive bushing.',l:''},'Kelly cock':{d:'a valve installed at one or both ends of the Kelly. When a high-pressure back-flow begins inside the drill stem, the valve is closed to keep pressure off the swivel and rotary hose.',l:''},'Kelly hose':{d:'also called the fluid hose or rotary hose. See rotary hose.',l:''},'Kelly saver sub':{d:'a sub that fits the drill stem between the Kelly and the drill pipe. Threads on the drill pipe mate with those of the sub, minimising wear on the Kelly.',l:''},'Kelly spinner':{d:'a pneumatically operated device mounted on top of the Kelly that, when actuated, causes the Kelly to turn or spin. it is useful when the Kelly or a joint of pipe is attached to it must be spun, that is, rotated rapidly for being made up.',l:''},'Kelly valve, lower':{d:'an essentially full-opening valve installed immediately below the Kelly, with outside diameter equal to the tool joint outside diameter. Valve can be stripped in the hole for snubbing operations. (API Recommended Practice 53).',l:''},'Kelvin temperature scale':{d:'a temperature scale with the degree interval of the Celsius scale and the zero point at absolute zero. On the Kelvin scale, water freezes at 273 K and boils at 373 K. See absolute temperature scale.',l:''},'key':{d:'1. a hook-shaped wrench that fits the square shoulder of a sucker rod and is used when rods are pulled or run into a pumping oilwell. Usually used in pairs; one key backs up and other breaks out or makes up the rod. Also called a rod wrench. 2. A slender strip of metal that is used to fasten a wheel or a gear onto a shaft. The key fits into slots in the shaft and in the wheel of gear.',l:''},'key seat':{d:'1. a channel or groove cut in the side of the hole of a well and parallel to the axis of the hole. A key seat results from the dragging of pipe on a sharp bend in the hole. 2. a groove cut parallel to the axis in a shaft or a pulley bore.',l:''},'kg':{d:'kilogram',l:''},'kick':{d:'an entry of water, gas, or other formation fluid into the well bore during drilling. It occurs because the pressure exerted by the column of drilling fluid is not great enough to overcome the pressure exerted by the fluids in the formation drilled. If prompt action is not taken to control the kick or kick the well, a blowout may occur.',l:''},'kill':{d:'1. In drilling, to prevent a threatened blowout by taking suitable preventative measures (e.g., to shut in the well with the Blowout Preventer, circulate the kick out ,and increase the weight of the drilling fluid). 2. In production to stop a well from producing oil and gas so that reconditioning of the well can proceed. Production is stopped by circulating water and fluid into the hole.',l:''},'kill drilling fluid density':{d:'the unit weight, e.g., pounds per gallon (lbs/gal) selected for the fluid to be used to contain a kicking formation. (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'kill line':{d:'a high-pressure fluid, circulate rate, expressed in fluid volume per unit time, which is to be used to circulate under kick condition, kill rate is usually some selected fraction of the circulating rate used while drilling. (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'kill rate circulating pressure':{d:'pump pressure required to circulate kill rate volume under non-kick conditions. (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'kill sheet':{d:'a printed form that contains blank spaces for recording information about killing an impending blowout, provided to remind personnel of necessary steps to kill a well.',l:''},'kill weight fluid':{d:'a fluid whose density creates a hydrostatic pressure equal to or greater than the pressure of the formations exposed to the well bore. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'kinematic viscosity':{d:'the absolute viscosity of a fluid divided by the density of the fluid at the temperature of viscosity measurement.',l:''},'kN':{d:'Kilo Newtons',l:''},'knife valve':{d:'a valve using a portal plate or blade to facilitate open and close operation. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'knockout':{d:'A knockout is a type or separator which falls into one of two categories: Free water and total liquid knockouts. (API Specification 12J). a) The free water knockout is a vessel used to separate free water from a flow stream of gas, oil and water. The gas and oil usually leave the vessel through the same outlet to be processed by other equipment. The water is removed for disposal. b) The total liquid knockout is normally used to remove the combined liquids from a gas stream.',l:''},'kPa':{d:'kilopascal',l:''},'laminar flow':{d:'a smooth flow of liquid in which no cross flow of fluid particles occurs between adjacent stream lines.',l:''},'land rig':{d:'any drilling rig that is located on dry land',l:''},'landing nipple':{d:'a receptacle in a production string with an internal profile to provide for latching and sealing of various types of plugs or valves. (API Recommended Practice 157).',l:''},'latch on':{d:'to attach elevators to section of pipe to pull it out of or run it into the hole.',l:''},'lay down pipe':{d:'to pull drill pipe or tubing from the hole and place it in a horizontal position on a pipe rack.',l:''},'lb':{d:'pound',l:''},'lb/ft³':{d:'pounds per cubic foot',l:''},'LCM ':{d:'Lost Circulation Material',l:''},'leak-off test':{d:'a gradual pressurising of the casing after the Blowout Preventers have been installed to permit estimation of the formation fracture pressure at the casing seat.',l:''},'legal entity':{d:'the division of the client company for the project. This may be a functional (e.g. Shell Trading) or regional division (e.g. Shell North America). There is no location information connected with a legal entity, so the same legal entity can be used in different regions and countries.',l:''},'lens-type trap':{d:'a hydrocarbon reservoir consisting of a porous, permeable, irregularly shaped sedimentary deposit surrounded by impervious rock.',l:''},'LIB ':{d:'Lead Impression Block',l:''},'lifting nipple':{d:'a short piece of pipe with a pronounced upset, or shoulder, on the upper end, screwed into drill pipe, drill collars, or casing to provide a positive grip for the elevators; also called a lifting sub or a hoisting plug.',l:''},'lifting sup':{d:'also called hoisting plug or lifting nipple.',l:''},'light crude oil':{d:'a crude oil of relatively high API gravity (usually 40 degrees or higher).',l:''},'lime':{d:'a caustic solid that consists primarily of calcium oxide (CaO). many forms of CaO are called lime, including the various chemical and physical forms of quicklime, hydrated lime, and even calcium lime.',l:''},'lime fluid':{d:'a drilling fluid that is treated with lime to provide a source of soluble calcium in the filtrate in order to obtain desirable fluid properties for drilling shale or clay formations.',l:''},'limestone':{d:'a sedimentary rock rich in calcium carbonate that sometimes serves a s reservoir rock for petroleum.',l:''},'limit switch':{d:'a hydraulic pneumatic or electrical switch that indicates the motion or position of a device. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'line hanger':{d:'a slip device that attaches the liner to the casing.',l:''},'liner section':{d:'the portion of the well that contains a short string of casing suspended inside an existing casing string. Liner sections do not extend to the surface.',l:''},'liquefied natural gas':{d:'a liquid composed chiefly of natural gas (i.e., mostly methane). Natural gas is liquefied to make it easy to transport if a pipeline is not feasible (as across a body of water). Not as easily liquefied as LPG, LNG must be put under low temperature and high pressure or under extremely low (cryogenic) temperature and close to atmospheric pressure to become liquefied.',l:''},'liquefied petroleum gas':{d:'a mixture of heavier, gaseous, paraffinic hydrocarbons, principally butane and propane. these gases, easily liquefied at moderate pressure, may be transported as liquids but converted to gases on release of the pressure. Thus, liquefied petroleum gas is a portable source of thermal energy that finds wide application in areas where it is impractical to distribute natural gas. It is also used as a fuel for internal-combustion engines and has many industrial and domestic uses. Principal sources are natural and refinery gas, from which the liquefied petroleum gases are separated by fractionation.',l:''},'liquid':{d:'a state of matter in which the shape of the given mass depends on the containing vessel, but the volume of the mass is independent of the vessel; a liquid is fluid that is almost incompressible.',l:''},'liquid-level gauge':{d:'any device connected to a vessel, coupled with either a float in the vessel or directly with the fluid therein, and calibrated to give a visual indication of the liquid level.',l:''},'lithology':{d:'1. the study of rocks, usually macroscopic. 2. the individual character of a rock in terms of mineral composition, structure and so forth.',l:''},'litre':{d:'a unit of metric measure of capacity equal to the volume occupied by 1 kg of water at 4ºC and at the standard atmospheric pressure of 760 mm.',l:''},'location':{d:'the place where a well is drilled; also called well site.',l:''},'locking mechanism':{d:'a support or restraint device. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'log':{d:'n: a systematic recording of data, such as a driller’s log, fluid log, electrical well log, or radioactivity log. Many different logs are run in the wells to obtain various characteristics of hole formations. v: to record data.',l:''},'longitude':{d:'the arc or portion of the earth’s equator intersected between the meridian of a given place and the prime meridian (at Greenwich, England) and expressed either in degrees or in time.',l:''},'loss of circulation':{d:'See lost circulation',l:''},'lost circulation':{d:'the quantities of whole fluid lost to a formation, usually in cavernous, fissured, or coarsely permeable beds, evidenced by the complete or partial failure of the fluid to return to the surface or partial failure of the fluid to return to the surface as it is being circulated in the hole. Lost circulation can lead to a blowout and, in general, reduce the efficiency of the drilling operation. Also called lost returns.',l:''},'lost circulation material':{d:'a substance added to cement slurries or drilling fluid to prevent the loss of cement or fluid to the formation. See bridging material.',l:''},'lost circulation plug':{d:'cement set across a formation that is taking excessively large amounts of drilling fluid during drilling operations.',l:''},'lost returns':{d:'loss of drilling fluids into the formation, resulting in a decrease in pit volume. (API Recommended Practice 53).',l:''},'lower ball joint':{d:'a device located above a subsea Blowout Preventer stack that permits relative angular movements of marine riser elements to reduce bending stresses caused by the vessel offset, vessel surge and sway, and environmental forces. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'lower Kelly cock':{d:'also called drill stem safety valve.',l:''},'lower marine riser package (LMRP)':{d:'the upper section of a two-section subsea BOP stack, consisting of the hydraulic connector, annular BOP, ball/flex joint riser adapter, flexible choke and kill lines, and subsea pods. This interfaces with the lower subsea BOP stack. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'LSYP':{d:'low shear yield point',l:''},'lubrication':{d:'alternately pumping a relatively small volume of liquid into a closed well bore system and waiting for the fluid to fall toward the bottom of the well; provides method for sealing off pressure and thus should be rated for highest anticipated pressure.',l:''},'LWD':{d:'logging while drilling',l:''},'m':{d:'meter',l:''},'MAASP ':{d:'Maximum Allowable Annular Surface Pressure',l:''},'macaroni-rig':{d:'a workover rig, usually lightweight, that is specially built to run a string of ¾-inch or 1-inch in diameter.',l:''},'magnetic brake':{d:'also called an electro-dynamic brake.',l:''},'make a connection':{d:'to attach a joint of drill pipe onto the drill stem suspended in the well bore to permit deepening the well bore by the length of the joint added (30 feet or 9 m).',l:''},'make a trip':{d:'to hoist the drill stem out of the well bore to perform one of a number of operations such as changing bits, taking a core, and so forth, and then to return the drill stem to the well bore.',l:''},'make hole':{d:'to deepen the hole made by the bit; to drill ahead.',l:''},'make-and-break':{d:'To connect and disconnect.',l:''},'manifold':{d:'an assemblage of pipe, valves and fittings by which fluid from one or more sources is selectively directed to various systems or components. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'manipulator valve':{d:'a three-position directional control valve that has the pressure inlet port blocked and the operator ports vented in the centre position. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'manometer':{d:'a U-shaped piece of glass tubing containing a liquid (usually water or mercury) that is used to measure the pressure of gases or liquids.',l:''},'marine riser connector':{d:'a fitting on top of the subsea Blowout Preventers to which the riser pipe is connected.',l:''},'marine riser system':{d:'the extension of the well bore from the subsea Blowout Preventer stack to the floating drilling vessel which provides for fluid returns to the drilling vessel, supports the choke, kill and control liens, guides tools into the well and serves as a running string for the Blowout Preventer stack. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'marl':{d:'a semisolid or unconsolidated clay, silt, or sand.',l:''},'marsh':{d:'a calibrated funnel used in field tests to determine the viscosity of drilling fluid.',l:''},'MASP ':{d:'Maximum Allowable Surface Pressure',l:''},'mast':{d:'a portable derrick that is capable of being erected as a unit, as distinguished from a standard derrick that cannot be raised to a working position as a unit. For transporting by land, the mast can be divided into two or more sections to avoid excessive length extending from truck beds on the highway.',l:''},'master bushing':{d:'a device that fits into the rotary table. It accommodates the slips and drives the Kelly bushing so that the rotary motion of the rotary table can be transmitted to the Kelly. Also called rotary bushing.',l:''},'master panel (hydraulic or electric)':{d:'the panel mounted in close proximity to the main accumulator unit. All control functions are operable from this panel, including all regulators and gauges.',l:''},'master valve':{d:'normally the lowermost valve(s) in the vertical run of the Christmas tree. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'material performance bases':{d:'capabilities which must be demonstrated, as a minimum, for material to satisfy the criteria of this standard. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'maximum allowable working pressure':{d:'the maximum allowable working pressure (MAWP) is the maximum pressure, permissible by the ASME Code at the top of the separator in its normal operating position for a designated temperature. (API Specification 12J).',l:''},'maximum anticipated surface pressure':{d:'the highest pressure predicted to be encountered at the surface of the well. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'Mcf':{d:'1,000 cubic feet of gas, commonly used to express the volume of gas produced, transmitted, or consumed in a given period.',l:''},'Mcf/d':{d:'1,000 ft3 of gas per day.',l:''},'MD ':{d:'Measured (Mean) Depth',l:''},'measuring tank':{d:'a calibrated tank that, by means of weirs, float switches, pressure switches, or similar devices, automatically measures the volume of liquid run in and then released. Measuring tanks are used in LACT systems. Also called metering tanks or dump tanks.',l:''},'MENA ':{d:'Middle East North Africa Region',l:''},'meridian':{d:'a north-south line from which longitudes and azimuths are reckoned.',l:''},'meta-centre':{d:'a point located somewhere on a line drawn vertically through the centre of buoyancy of the hull of a floating vessel with the hull in one position (e.g. level) and then another (e.g. inclined). when the hull inclines slightly to a new position, the centre of buoyancy of the hull also moves to a new position. If a second line is drawn vertically through the new centre of buoyancy, it intersects the first line at a point called the meta-centre. Location of the meta-centre is important because it affects the stability of floating vessels (such as mobile offshore drilling rigs).',l:''},'metamorphic rock':{d:'a rock derived from pre-existing rocks by mineralogical, chemical, and structural alterations caused by processes within the earth’s crust. Marble is a metamorphic rock.',l:''},'methane':{d:'a light, gaseous, flammable paraffin hydrocarbon. Ch4,that has a boiling point of -258ºF and is the chief component of natural gas and an important basic hydrocarbon for petrochemical manufacture.',l:''},'metre':{d:'the fundamental unit of length in the metric system. Its symbol is m. It is equal to about 3.28 feet, 39.37 inches, or 100 centimetres.',l:''},'metric ton':{d:'a measurement equal to 1000kg or 2,204.6 lb avoirdupois. In many oil-producing countries, production is reported in metric tons. One metric ton is equivalent to about 7.4 barrels (42 US gal = 1 bbl) of crude oil with a specific gravity of 0.84, or 36º API. In the SI system, it is called a tonne.',l:''},'MFR':{d:'multifrequency resistivity',l:''},'mica':{d:'a silicate mineral characterised by sheet cleavage. Biotite is ferro-magnesian black mica, and muscovite is potassic white mica. Sometimes mica is used as lost circulation material in drilling.',l:''},'micron':{d:'one-millionth of a metre; a metric unit of measure of length equal to 0.001 mm.',l:''},'migration':{d:'the movement of oil from the area in which it was formed to a reservoir rock where it can accumulate.',l:''},'millidarcy':{d:'one-thousandth of a darcy.',l:''},'Mine Safety and Health Administration':{d:'a US government agency that evaluates research in the causes of occupational diseases and accidents. Head-quarters in Arlington, Virginia, MSHA is responsible for administration of the certification of respiratory safety equipment.',l:''},'mini or auxiliary remote panel':{d:'a limited function panel mounted in a remote location for use as an emergency backup. On an offshore rig it is normally located in the Tool pusher’s office, and on a land rig, at least 100 feet from the prevailing wind. ',l:''},'minimum internal yield pressure':{d:'the lowest pressure at which permanent deformation will occur. (API Recommended Practice 53).',l:''},'MIRU ':{d:'Move In, Rig-Up',l:''},'mixing system':{d:'a system that mixes a measured amount of water soluble lubricant and optional glycol to feed water and delivers it to a storage tank or reservoir. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'mixing tank':{d:'any tank or vessel used to mix components of a substance (as in the mixing of additives with drilling fluid).',l:''},'MM ':{d:'Multi Mode – as in fiber optic',l:''},'MMcf':{d:'million cubic feet; a common unit of measurement for large quantities of gas.',l:''},'MMscf':{d:'million standard cubic feet per day.',l:''},'mobile offshore drilling rig':{d:'a drilling rig that is used exclusively to drill offshore wells and that floats upon the surface of the water when being moved from one location to another. It may or may not float once drilling begins. The drill ship, semi-submersible drilling rig, and jack-up drilling rig are all mobile rigs; a platform rig is not.',l:''},'mol':{d:'mole',l:''},'mole':{d:'the fundamental unit of mass of a substance. Its symbol is mol. A mole of any substance is the number of grams or pounds indicated by its molecular weight. For example, H20 has a molecular weight of approximately 18. Therefore, a gram mole of water is 18 grams of water; a pound mole of water is 18 pounds of water.',l:''},'Monel steel':{d:'a nickel-base alloy containing copper, iron, manganese, silicon, and carbon. Non-magnetic drill collars are often made of this material.',l:''},'monkey board':{d:'the Derrickman’s working platform. As pipe or tubing is run into or out of the hole, the Derrickman must handle the top end of the pipe, which may be as high as 90 feet (27 m) in the derrick or mast. The monkey board provides a small platform to raise him to the proper height for handling the top of the pipe.',l:''},'montmorillonite':{d:'a clay mineral often used as an additive to drilling fluid. It is a hydrous aluminium silicate capable of reacting with such substances as magnesium and calcium. See bentonite.',l:''},'moon pool':{d:'a walled round hole or well in the hull of a drill ship (usually in the centre) through which the drilling assembly and other assemblies pass while a well is being drilled, completed, or abandoned from the drill ship.',l:''},'moored vessels':{d:'offshore floating drilling vessels which rely on anchors, chains, and mooring lines extended to the ocean floor to keep the vessel at a constant location relative to the ocean floor. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'motion compensator':{d:'any device (such as a bumper sub or heave compensator) that serves to maintain constant weight on the bit in spite of vertical motion of a floating offshore drilling rig.',l:''},'motor-generator rig':{d:'a drilling rig driven by electric motors with current supplied by engine-driven generators at the rig.',l:''},'mousehole':{d:'an opening through the rig floor, usually lined with pipe, into which a length of drill pipe is placed temporarily for later connection to the drill string.',l:''},'Mpa':{d:'megapascal',l:''},'MPD ':{d:'Managed Pressure Drilling',l:''},'MSA':{d:'Multi-Station Analysis',l:''},'Mscf/D':{d:' thousand standard cubic feet per day.',l:''},'MSHA':{d:'Milne Safety and Health Administration.',l:''},'MSL ':{d:'Mean Sea Level – often used as depth reference offshore',l:''},'MST ':{d:'Mechanical Setting Tool',l:''},'mud':{d:'See Drilling Fluids',l:''},'mud hopper':{d:'See hopper.',l:''},'mud motor':{d:'A downhole component of the BHA which rotates the bit without having to turn the rotary table. The term is sometimes applied to both positive displacement motors and turbodrills.',l:''},'mud-gas separator':{d:'a device that separates gas from the fluid coming out of a well when gas cutting has occurred or when a kick is being circulated out.',l:''},'multiplex':{d:'a system that uses multiple electronic signals that are coded and transmitted through a conductor pair. This eliminates the requirement of a dedicated conductor pair for each required signal. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'MWD':{d:'measurement while drilling',l:''},'NACE':{d:'National Association of Corrosion Engineers.',l:''},'National Association of Corrosion Engineers':{d:'organisation whose function is to establish standards and recommended practices for the field of corrosion control. It is based in Houston, Texas.',l:''},'natural gas':{d:'a highly compressible, highly expandable mixture of hydrocarbons having a low specific gravity and occurring naturally in gaseous form Besides hydrocarbon gases, natural gas may contain appreciable quantities of nitrogen, helium, carbon dioxide, hydrogen sulphide, and water vapour. Although gaseous at normal temperatures and pressures, the gases comprising the mixture that is natural gas are variable in form and may be found either as gases or as liquids under suitable conditions of temperature and pressure.',l:''},'natural gas liquids':{d:'those hydrocarbons liquefied at the surface in field facilities or in gas processing plants. Natural gas liquids include propane, butane, and natural gasoline.',l:''},'needle valve':{d:'a form of globe valve that contains a sharp-pointed, needle-like plug that is driven into and out of a cone-shaped seat to accurately control a relatively small rate of flow of a fluid. In a fuel injector, the fuel pressure forces the needle valve off its seat to allow injection to take place.',l:''},'newton':{d:'the unit of force in the metric system; its symbol is N. A Newton is the force required to accelerate an object of 1 kilogram mass to a velocity of 1 metre per second in 1 second.',l:''},'newton-metre':{d:'also called a joule. See joule.',l:''},'Newtonian fluid':{d:'a fluid in which the viscosity remains constant for all rates of shear if constant conditions of temperature and pressure are maintained. Most drilling fluids behave as non-Newtonian fluids, as their viscosity is not constant but varies with the rate of shear.',l:''},'nipple up':{d:'in drilling, to assemble the Blowout Preventer stack on the well head at the surface.',l:''},'nominal size':{d:'a designated size that may be different from the actual size.',l:''},'non-magnetic drill collar':{d:'a drill collar made of an alloy that does not affect the readings of a magnetic compass placed within it to obtain subsurface indications of the direction of a deviated well bore. Used in directional drilling.',l:''},'non-porous':{d:'containing no interstices; having no pores.',l:''},'non-retrievable control pod':{d:'a pod that is fixed in place on the LRMP and not retrievable. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'normal circulation':{d:'the smooth, uninterrupted circulation of drilling fluid down the drill stem, out the bit, up the annular space between the pipe and the hole, and back to the surface.',l:''},'normal formation pressure':{d:'formation fluid pressure equivalent to 0.465 psi per foot of depth from the surface. If the formation pressure is 4,650 psi at 10,000 feet, it is considered normal.',l:''},'northing':{d:'map coordinate measured northward from East/West line',l:''},'nozzle':{d:'1. a passageway through jet bits that allows the drilling fluid to reach the bottom of the hole and flush the cuttings through the annuls. Nozzles comes in different sizes that can be interchanged on the bit to allow more or less flow. 2. the part of the fuel system of an engine that has small holes in it to permit fuel to enter the cylinder. Properly known as a fuel-injection nozzle. Also called a spray valve. The needle valve is directly above the nozzle.',l:''},'NP ':{d:'Neutral Point – between compression and tension in drill string, tubing and casing',l:''},'NPT ':{d:'Non Productive Time',l:''},'NRV ':{d:'Non-Return Valve',l:''},'NU ':{d:'Non-Upset (on tubing joint)',l:''},'NVL ':{d:'Net Vertical Lift (ESP related)',l:''},'O \u0026 G':{d:'oil and gas; used in drilling reports.',l:''},'OD':{d:'outside diameter',l:''},'offset well':{d:'a well drilled on a tract of land proximate to another owner\u0027s tract on which there is a producing well',l:''},'offset-well data':{d:'information obtained from wells that are drilled in an area close to where a well is being drilled or worked over. Such information can be very helpful in determining how a particular well will behave or react to certain treatments or techniques applied to it.',l:''},'offshore':{d:'the geographic area which lies seaward of the coastline. In general, the term coastline means the line of ordinary low water along that portion of the coast that is in direct contact with the open sea or the line marking the seaward limit of inland waters.',l:''},'offshore drilling':{d:'drilling for oil in an ocean, gulf, or sea, usually on the continental shelf. A drilling unit for offshore operations may be a mobile floating vessel with a ship or barge hull, a semi-submersible or submersible base, a self-propelled or towed structure with jacking legs (jack-up drilling rig), or a permanent structure used as a production platform when drilling from mobile floating vessels or form a jack-up vessel, while development wells are drilled from platforms.',l:''},'offshore platform':{d:'permanently installed bottom supported or connected offshore structure, equipped with drilling and/or production equipment for drilling and/or development of offshore oil and gas reservoirs. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'offshore rig':{d:'any of various types of drilling structures designed for use in drilling wells in oceans, seas, bays, gulfs, and so forth. Offshore rigs include platforms, jack-up drilling rigs, semi-submersible drilling rigs, submersible drill rigs and drill ships.',l:''},'OH':{d:'open hole; used in drilling reports.',l:''},'oil and gas separator':{d:'an item of production equipment used to separate liquid components of the well stream from the gaseous elements. Separators are either vertical or horizontal and either cylindrical or spherical in shape. separation is accomplished principally by gravity, the heavier liquids falling to the bottom and the gas rising to the top. a float valve or other liquid-level control regulates the level of oil in the bottom of the separator.',l:''},'oil drilling fluid':{d:'a drilling fluid in which oil is the continuous phase. Oil-base fluid and invert-emulsion fluid are types of oil fluids. They are useful in drilling certain formations that may be difficult or costly to drill with water-base fluid.',l:''},'oil field':{d:'the surface area overlying an oil reservoir or reservoirs. Commonly, the term includes not only the surface area, but also the reservoir, the wells, and the production equipment.',l:''},'oil sand':{d:'1. a sandstone that yields oil. 2. (by extension) any reservoir that yields oil, whether or not it is sandstone.',l:''},'oil shale':{d:'a formation containing hydrocarbons that cannot be recovered by an ordinary oilwell but cannot be recovered by an ordinary oilwell but can be mined. After processing, the hydrocarbons and treatment of oil shale has until recently been too great to compete with the cost of oilwell drilling.',l:''},'oil-base drilling fluid':{d:'an oil that contains from less that 2 percent up to 5 percent water. The water is spread out, or dispersed, in the oil as small droplets.',l:''},'oil-emulsion drilling fluid':{d:'a water-base fluid in which water is the continuous phase and oil is the dispersed phase. The oil is spread out, or dispersed, in the water in small droplets, which are tightly emulsified so that they do not settle out. Because of its lubricating abilities, an oil-emulsion fluid increases the drilling rate and ensures better hole conditions than other fluids.',l:''},'oil-water contact':{d:'the point or plane at which the bottom of an oil sand contacts the top of a water sand in a reservoir; the oil-water interface.',l:''},'oilwell pump':{d:'any pump, surface or subsurface, that is used to lift fluids from the reservoir to the surface. See sucker rod pumping and hydraulic pumping.',l:''},'on-suction':{d:'of a tank, open to pump suction.',l:''},'open formation':{d:'a petroleum-bearing rock with good porosity and permeability.',l:''},'open hole':{d:'1. any well bore in which casing has not been set. 2. open and cased hole in which no drill pipe or tubing is suspended. 3. the portion of the well bore that has no casing.',l:''},'open hole section':{d:'the portion of the well without casing',l:''},'open-circuit regulator':{d:'also called demand regulator.',l:''},'opening ratio':{d:'the ratio of the well pressure to the pressure required to open the Blowout Preventer. (API Recommended Practice 53).',l:''},'operating company':{d:'See operator.',l:''},'operating pressure':{d:'the operating pressure is the pressure in the vessel during normal operation. The operating pressure shall not exceed the MAWP, and is usually kept at a suitable level below the setting of the pressure relieving devices to prevent their frequent opening. (API Specification 12J).',l:''},'operational survey':{d:'the actual drilled trajectory of the well',l:''},'operator':{d:'the person or company, either proprietor or lessee, actually operating an oilwell or lease. Generally, the oil company by whim the drilling contractor is engaged.',l:''},'organic rock':{d:'rock materials produced by a plant or animal life (coal, petroleum, limestone, etc).',l:''},'organic theory':{d:'an explanation of the origin of petroleum, which holds that the hydrogen and the carbon that make up petroleum come from plants and animals of land and sea. Furthermore, the theory holds that more of this organic material comes from very tiny creatures of swamp and sea than comes from larger creatures of land.',l:''},'OSS ':{d:'Optical Sensing Systems (part of ICT product line)',l:''},'out-of-gauge hole':{d:'a hole that is not gauge, that is, of a size smaller or larger than the diameter of the bit used to drill the hole.',l:''},'outer barrel':{d:'the part of a telescopic slip joint on a marine riser which is attached to tension lines. Tension is transferred through the outer barrel into the riser. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'over-gauge hole':{d:'a hole whose diameter is larger than the diameter of the bit used to drill it. An over-gauge hole can occur when a bit is not properly stabilised or does not have enough weight put on it.',l:''},'overbalance':{d:'the amount by which pressure exerted by the hydrostatic head of fluid in the well bore exceeds formation pressure. (API Recommended Practice 59).',l:''},'overboard (diverter) line':{d:'refer to vent line.',l:''},'overburden':{d:'the pressure on a formation due to the weight of the earth material above that formation. For practical purposes, this pressure can be estimated at 1 psi/ft of depth. (API Recommended Practice 53).',l:''},'overburden pressure':{d:'the pressure exerted by the overburden on the formation targeted for drilling.',l:''},'overgauge':{d:'the amount of washout expected while drilling',l:''},'overshot':{d:'a fishing tool that is attached to tubing or drill pipe and lowered over the outside of the wall of pipe or sucker rods lost or stuck in the well bore. A friction device in the overshot, usually either a basket or a spiral grapple, firmly grips the pipe, allowing the lost fish to be pulled from the hole.',l:''},'P \u0026 A ':{d:'Plug and Abandon – to secure an old/unwanted well.',l:''},'packed pendulum assembly':{d:'a bottom hole assembly in which pendulum-length collars are swung below a regular packed-hole assembly. The pendulum portion of the assembly is used to reduce hole angle; it is then removed, and the packed-hole assembly is run above the bit.',l:''},'packed-hole assembly':{d:'a drill stem that consists of stabilisers and special drill collars and is used to maintain the proper angle and course of the hole. This assembly is often necessary in crooked hole country.',l:''},'Packer':{d:'a piece of down hole equipment, consisting of a sealing device, and an inside passage for fluids, used to block the flow of fluids through the annular space between the tubing and the wall of the well bore by sealing off the space between them. It is usually made up in the tubing string some distance above the producing zone. A sealing element expands to prevent fluid flow except through the inside bore of the packer and into the tubing. Packers are classified according to configuration, use, and method of setting and whether or not they are retrievable (that is, whether they can be removed when necessary, or whether they must be milled or drilled out and thus destroyed):',l:''},'Packer test':{d:'application of hydraulic pressure either through the tubing or annulus to assure that the packer is properly set and sealed. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'packing element':{d:'the annular sealing device in an annular Blowout Preventer or diverter. (API Recommend Practice 64)',l:''},'packoff or stripper':{d:'a devise with an elastomer packing element that depends on pressure below the packing to effect a seal in the annulus. Used primarily to run or pull pipe under low or moderate pressures. This device is not dependable for service under high differential pressures. (API Recommended Practice 53)',l:''},'parent interval':{d:'A kind of interval that serves as a container for other intervals.',l:''},'part':{d:'an individual piece used in the assembly of a single equipment unit. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'partial pressure':{d:'the pressure exerted by one specific component of a gaseous mixture.',l:''},'Pascal':{d:'the accepted metric unit of measurement for pressure and stress and a component in the measurement of viscosity. A Pascal is equal to a force of 1 Newton acting on an area if 1 square metre. It is symbol Pa.',l:''},'PBR ':{d:'Polished Bore Receptacle',l:''},'PCD ':{d:'Pitch Circle Diameter',l:''},'PCP ':{d:'Progressing Cavity Pump',l:''},'PDC ':{d:'Polycrystalline Diamond Compact – rock bit inserts',l:''},'pendulum assembly':{d:'a bottom hole assembly composed of a bit and several large-diameter drill collars; it may have one or more stabilisers installed in the drill collar string. The assembly works on the principle of the pendulum effect.',l:''},'pendulum effect':{d:'the tendency of the drill stem - bit, drill collars, drill pipe, and Kelly - to hang in a vertical position due to the force of gravity.',l:''},'penetration rate':{d:'See rate of penetration',l:''},'percussion drilling':{d:'1. Cable-tool-drilling. 2. Rotary drilling in which a special tool called a hammer drill is used in combination with a roller cone bit.',l:''},'perforate':{d:'to pierce the casing wall and cement to provide holes through which formation fluids may enter or to provide holes in the casing so that materials may be introduced into the annulus between the casing and the wall of the borehole. Perforating is accomplished by lowering into the well a perforating gun, or perforator, that fires electricity detonated bullets or shaped charges from the surface.',l:''},'period of roll':{d:'the time required for a floating offshore drilling rig to roll from one side to the other and back.',l:''},'permanent guide base':{d:'a structure attached to and installed with the foundation pile when a well is drilled from an offshore drilling rig. It is seated in the temporary guide base and serves as a well head housing. Also, guidelines are attached to it so that equipment (such as the Blowout Preventer) may be guided into place on the well head.',l:''},'permeability':{d:'1. A measure of the ease in which fluids can flow through a porous rock. 2. The fluid conductivity of a porous medium. 3. The ability of a fluid to flow within the interconnected pore network of a porous medium. See absolute permeability, and effective permeability.',l:''},'PES ':{d:'Precision Energy Services',l:''},'petroleum geology':{d:'the study of oil-and gas bearing rock formations. It deals with the origin, occurrence, movement, and accumulation of hydrocarbon fuels.',l:''},'pH value':{d:'a unit of measure of the acid or alkaline condition of a substance. A neutral solution (such as pure water) has a pH of 7; acid solutions are less than 7. The pH scale is a logarithmic scale; a substance with a pH 9 is more than twice as alkaline as a substance with a pH of 8.',l:''},'piggyback':{d:'(nautical) to install anchors behind each other in tandem on the same mooring line.',l:''},'pilot bit':{d:'a bit placed on a special device called a hole opener that serves to guide the devise into an already existing hole that is to be opened (made larger in diameter). The pilot bit merely guides, or pilots, the cutters on the hole opener into the existing hole so that the hole-opening cutters can enlarge the hole to the desired size.',l:''},'pilot fluid':{d:'hydraulic control fluid that is dedicated to the pilot supply system. (API Recommended practice 16E)',l:''},'pilot line':{d:'a hydraulic line that transmits pilot fluid to a control valve. Pilot lines are normally grouped in a common bundle or umbilical.',l:''},'pilot response time':{d:'for subsea systems, the time it takes when the hydraulic function valve is activated on the surface for the signal to travel through the pilot line and activate a control panel in the pod. (API Recommended Practise 16E)',l:''},'pin-drive master bushing':{d:'a master bushing that has four drive holes corresponding to the four pins on the bottom of the pin-drive Kelly bushing.',l:''},'pinion':{d:'1. A gear with a small number of teeth designed to mesh with a larger wheel or rack. 2. The smaller of a pair or the smallest of a train of gear wheels.',l:''},'pipe':{d:'a long hollow cylinder, usually steel, through which fluids are conducted. Oil field tubular goods are casing (including liners), drill pipe, tubing, or line pipe. Casing, tubing, and drill pipe are designated by external diameter. Because lengths of pipe are joined by external-diameter couplings threaded by standard tools, an increase in the wall thickness can be obtained only by decreasing the internal diameter. Thus, the external diameter is the same for all weights of the same-size pipe. Weight is expressed in pounds per foot or kilograms per metre. Grading depends on the yield strength of the steel.',l:''},'pipe protector':{d:'a protector that prevents drill pipe from rubbing against the hole or against the casing. pipe rack',l:''},'pipe rack':{d:'a horizontal support for tubular goods.',l:''},'pipe ram':{d:'a sealing component for a Blowout Preventer or well head. Unless special rams accommodating various pipe sizes are used, separate rams are necessary for each size (outside diameter) pipe in use',l:''},'pipe ram BOP':{d:'a hydraulically operated system typically having two opposed ram assemblies that move radically inward to close on pipe in the well bore and seal he annular space. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'pipe ram preventer':{d:'a Blowout Preventer that uses pipe rams as the closing elements.',l:''},'pipe upset':{d:'that part of the pipe that has an abrupt increase of dimension.',l:''},'pipe wiper':{d:'a flexible disk-shaped device, usually made of rubber, with a hole in the centre through which drill pipe or tubing passes, used to wipe of fluid, or other liquid from the pipe as the pipe is pulled from the hole.',l:''},'pit level':{d:'height of drilling fluid in the fluid pits.',l:''},'pit-level indicator':{d:'one of a series of devices that continuously monitor the level of the drilling fluid in the fluid tanks. The indicator usually consists of float devices in the fluid tanks that sense the fluid level and transmit data to a recording and alarm device (a pit-volume recorder) mounted near the Driller\u0027s position on the rig floor. If the fluid level drops too low or rises too high, the alarm sounds to warn the Driller that he may be either losing circulation or taking a kick.',l:''},'pit-level recorder':{d:'the gauge at',l:''},'plastic viscosity':{d:'an absolute flow property indicating the flow resistance of certain types of fluids. Plastic viscosity is a measure of shearing stress.',l:''},'platform rig':{d:'a rig that rests on a platform above the water, supported by steel pillars',l:''},'PLM ':{d:'Product Line Manager',l:''},'plug':{d:'any object or device that blocks a hole or passageway (as a cement plug in a borehole).',l:''},'plug and abandon':{d:'to place a cement plug into a dry hole and abandon it.',l:''},'plug valve':{d:'a valve whose mechanism consists of a plug with a hole through it on the same axis as the direction of fluid flow. Turning the plug 90 degrees opens or closes the valve. The valve may or may not be full opening. (API Recommended Practice 53).',l:''},'pneumatic':{d:'operated by air pressure.',l:''},'pneumatic control':{d:'a control valve that is actuated by air. Several pneumatic controls are used on drilling rigs to actuate rig components (clutches, hoists, engines, pumps, etc.).',l:''},'POB ':{d:'515 Post Oak, Weatherford Headquarters in Galleria area of Houston',l:''},'pod':{d:'see control pod.',l:''},'POH (POOH) ':{d:'Pull Out Of Hole',l:''},'poise':{d:'the viscosity of a liquid in which a force of 1 dyne (unit of measurement of small amounts of force) exerted tangentially on a surface of 1 cm² of either of two parallel planes 1 cm apart will move one plane at the rate of 1 cm per second in reference to the other plane, with the space between the two planes filled with the liquid.',l:''},'polymer':{d:'a substance that consists of large molecules formed from smaller molecules in repeating structural units. In petroleum refining, heat and pressure are used to polymerise light hydrocarbons into larger molecules, such as those that make up high-octane gasoline. In oil field operations, various types of organic polymers are used to thicken drilling fluid, fracturing fluid, acid, and other liquids. In petrochemical production, polymer hydrocarbons are used as the basis for plastics.',l:''},'polymer units':{d:'a drilling fluid which has been added a polymer, a chemical that consists of large molecules that were formed from small molecules in repeating structural units, to increase the viscosity of the fluid.',l:''},'POP ':{d:'Pump Open Plugs (Weatherford Petroline product)',l:''},'pop valve':{d:'a spring-loaded safety valve that opens automatically when pressure exceeds the limits for which the valve is set. It is used as a safety device on pressurised vessels and other equipment to prevent damage for excessive pressure. It is also called a relief valve or a safety valve.',l:''},'poppet valve':{d:'a device that controls the rate of flow of fluid in a line or opens or shuts off the flow of fluid completely . When open, the sealing surface of the valve is moved away from a seat; when closed, the sealing surface contacts the seat to shut off flow. Usually, the direction of movement of the valve is perpendicular to the seat. Poppet valves are used extensively as pneumatic (air) controls on drilling rigs and as intake and exhaust valves in most internal-combustion engines.',l:''},'pore':{d:'an opening or space within rock or mass of rocks, usually small and often filled with some fluid (water, oil, gas, or all three).',l:''},'pore pressure':{d:'pressure exerted by the fluids within the pore space of a formation. Also called formation pressure.',l:''},'pore pressure (formation pressure)':{d:'pressure exerted by the fluids within the pore space of a formation.',l:''},'porosity':{d:'the condition of something that contains pores (such as rock formation).',l:''},'Portland cement':{d:'the cement most widely used in oil wells. It is made from raw materials such as limestone, clay or shale, and iron ore.',l:''},'positive-displacement motor':{d:'usually called a Dyna-drill. See Dyna Drill.',l:''},'possum belly':{d:'1. receiving tank situated at the end of the fluid return line. The flow of fluid comes into the bottom of the device and travels over baffles to control fluid over the shale shaker. 2. a metal box under a truck bed that holds pipeline repair tools.',l:''},'post weld heat treatment':{d:'any heat treatment subsequent to welding, including stress relief.',l:''},'potable water':{d:'a water supply that is acceptably pure for human consumption. on an offshore rig, it is usually produced by water-makers and uses a supply water for mixing control fluid for a subsea control system. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'POTH ':{d:'Pull Out of the Tubing Hanger',l:''},'pounds per square inch gauge':{d:'the pressure in a vessel or container as registered on a gauge attached to the container. the pressure reading does not include the pressure of the atmosphere outside the container.',l:''},'power fluid':{d:'pressurised hydraulic fluid dedicated to the direct operation of functions. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'power tongs':{d:'a wrench that is used to make up or break out drill pipe, tubing, or casing on which the torque is provided by air or fluid pressure. Conventional tongs are operated by mechanical pull provided by a jerk line connected to a cat-head.',l:''},'ppf ':{d:'psi per foot – density derivative from mud balance to calculate pressure',l:''},'ppg':{d:'pounds per gallon',l:''},'ppm':{d:'parts per million',l:''},'pre-charge':{d:'se accumulator pre-charge.',l:''},'pressure':{d:'the force that fluid (liquid or gas) exerts uniformly in all directions within a vessel, pipe, hole in the ground, and so forth, such as that exerted against the liner wall of a tank or that exerted against the liner wall of a tank or that exerted on the bottom of the well bore by drilling fluid. Pressure is expressed in terms of force exerted per unit of area, as pounds per square inch (psi) or grams or kilograms per square centimetre.',l:''},'pressure differential':{d:'See differential pressure.',l:''},'pressure drop':{d:'a loss of pressure, resulting from friction, sustained by a fluid passing through a line, valve, fitting, or other device.',l:''},'pressure drop vs. flow rate':{d:'a record of the pressure decline after halting or reducing fluid injection compared to the volume, mass, or weight of a fluid passing through any conductor per unit of time',l:''},'pressure equalisation valve (dump valve)':{d:'a device used to control bottom riser annulus pressure by establishing direct communication with the sea. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'pressure gauge':{d:'an instrument that measures fluid pressure and usually registers the difference between atmospheric pressure and the pressure of the fluid by indicating the effect of such pressures on a measuring element ( a column of liquid, a Bourdon tube, a weighted piston, a diaphragm, ot other pressure-sensitive device).',l:''},'pressure gradient':{d:'a scale of pressure differences in which there is a uniform variation of pressure from point to point. for example, the pressure gradient of a column of water is about 0.433 psi/ft of vertical elevation. The normal pressure gradient in a formation is equivalent to the pressure exerted at any given depth by a column of 10 percent salt water extending from that depth to the surface (0.465 psi/ft or 10.518 kPa/m).',l:''},'pressure loss':{d:'1. a reduction in the amount of force a fluid exerts against a surface, usually occurring because the fluid is moving against the surface. 2. the amount of pressure gauge when drilling fluid is being circulated by the fluid pump. Pressure losses occur as the fluid is circulated. pressure relief valve',l:''},'pressure relief valve':{d:'a valve that opens at a preset pressure to relieve excessive pressures within a vessel or line. Also called a relief line, safety valve, or pop valve. pressure retaining part(s) or member(s). n pl.: those parts not exposed to well bore fluid s whose failure to function as intended would result in a release well bore fluid to the environment such as closure bolts, clamps. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'pressure test, blowout preventer':{d:'the process of pressure testing internally a Blowout Preventer or Blowout preventer assemble. (API Recommended Practise 57)',l:''},'pressure vessel quality':{d:'metallic material whose integrity is such that it can be used to safety contain pressure without risk of leakage or rupture. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'pressure vs. flow rate':{d:'a record of the amount of pressure compared to the volume, mass, or weight of a fluid passing through any conductor per unit of time',l:''},'pressure-differentially-set valve':{d:'a valve that is operated when its actuator senses a change in pressure of a pre-set limit. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'preventer':{d:'shortened form of Blowout Preventer. See blowout preventer',l:''},'preventive maintenance':{d:'a system conducting regular checks and testing of equipment to permit replacement or repair of weakened or faulty parts before failure of the equipment results.',l:''},'primary cementing':{d:'the cementing operation that takes place immediately after the casing has been run into the hole; used to provide a protective sheath around the casing, to segregate the producing formation, and to prevent the undesirable migration of fluids. See secondary cementing and squeeze cementing.',l:''},'primary mover':{d:'an internal-combustion engine that is the source of power for a drilling rig and oilwell drilling.',l:''},'primary well control':{d:'prevention of formation fluid flow by maintaining a hydrostatic pressure equal to or greater than formation pressure. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'producing zone':{d:'the zone or formation from which oil and gas is produces.',l:''},'production packer':{d:'a devise installed in wells to effect a seal between the tubing string(s) and casing.',l:''},'proposed plan':{d:'the projected wellpath that\u0027s used to plan the well before drilling begins',l:''},'propping agent':{d:'a granular substance (sand grains, aluminium pellets, or other material) that is carried in suspension by the fracturing fluid and that serves to keep the cracks open when fracturing fluid is withdrawn after fracture treatment.',l:''},'psi':{d:'pounds per square inch',l:''},'psi-ft.':{d:'pounds per square inch per foot',l:''},'psia ':{d:'pounds per square inch absolute',l:''},'psig':{d:'pounds per square inch gauge.',l:''},'PTI ':{d:'Petro Technologies Incorporated',l:''},'pto':{d:'power take off.',l:''},'pull it green':{d:'to pull a bit from the hole for replacement before it is greatly worn.',l:''},'pull out':{d:'See come out of the hole.',l:''},'pump liner':{d:'a cylindrical, accurately machined, metallic section that forms the working barrel of some reciprocating pumps. Liners are an inexpensive means of replacing worn cylinder surfaces, and in some pumps they provide a method of conveniently changing the displacement and capacity of the pumps.',l:''},'pump pressure':{d:'fluid pressure arising from the action of a pump.',l:''},'pump-through tubing plug':{d:'a plug set inside the tubing string which will not permit back flow, but will permit pumping through from the top side. (API Recommended Practice 57).',l:''},'pumping unit':{d:'the machine that imparts reciprocating motion to a string of sucker rods extending to the positive-displacement pump at the bottom of a well; usually a beam arrangement driven by a crank attached to a speed reducer.',l:''},'pup joint':{d:'a length of drill pipe, tubing, or casing shorter than 30 feet.',l:''},'PV':{d:'plastic viscosity',l:''},'PVT':{d:'pressure/volume/temperature',l:''},'QLS ':{d:'Quick Lock System - Petroline',l:''},'qualified personnel':{d:'individuals with characteristics or abilities gained through training, experience, or both, as measured against the manufacturers established requirements. (API Specification 16A).',l:''},'quartz':{d:'hard mineral composed of silicon dioxide; a common component in igneous, metamorphic, and sedimentary rocks.',l:''},'R':{d:'Rankin. See Rankin temperature scale.',l:''},'rabbit':{d:'1. a small plug that is run through a flow line to clean the line or to test for obstructions. 2. any plug left unintentionally in a pipeline during construction (as, a rabbit that ran into the pipe).',l:''},'rack pipe':{d:'1. to place pipe withdrawn from the hole on a pipe rack. 2. to stand pipe on the derrick floor when coming out of the hole.',l:''},'ram':{d:'the closing and sealing component on a Blowout Preventer. One of three types – blind, pipe, or shear – may be installed in several preventers mounted in a stack on top of the well bore. Blind rams, when closed, form a seal on a hole that has no drill pipe in it; pipe rams, when closed, seal around the pipe; shear rams cut through drill pipe and then form a seal.',l:''},'ram blowout preventer':{d:'a Blowout Preventer that uses rams to seal off pressure on a hole that is with our without pipe. also called a ram preventer.',l:''},'Ram preventer':{d:'also called a ram Blowout Preventer.',l:''},'Rankin temperature scale':{d:'a temperature scale with the degree interval of the Fahrenheit scale and the zero point at absolute zero. On the Rankin scale, water freezes at 491.60º and boils at 671.69º. See absolute temperature scale.',l:''},'rat-hole':{d:'n: 1. a hole in the rig floor, 30-35 feet (9-11 m) deep, which is lined with casing that projects above the floor and into which the Kelly and swivel are placed when hoisting operations are in progress. 2. a hole of a diameter smaller than the main hole and drilled in the bottom of the main hole. v: to reduce the size of the well bore and drill ahead.',l:''},'rat-hole connection':{d:'the addition of a length of drill pipe or tubing to the active string. The length to be added is placed in the rat-hole, made up to the Kelly, pulled out of the rat-hole, and made up into the string.',l:''},'rate of penetration':{d:'a measure of the speed at which the bit drills into formations, usually expressed in feet (metres) per hour or minutes per foot (metre).',l:''},'rated working pressure':{d:'the maximum internal pressure equipment is designed to contain and/or control. Rated working pressure is not to be confused with test pressure. (API Specification 16A).',l:''},'RDMO ':{d:'Rig Down, Move Off',l:''},'readback':{d:'an indication of a remote condition.',l:''},'ream':{d:'to enlarge the well bore by drilling it again with a special bit. Often a rat-hole is reamed or opened to the same size as the main well bore. See rat-hole.',l:''},'records':{d:'retrievable information. (API Specification 16A).',l:''},'reel (hose of cable)':{d:'a reel, usually power driven, that stores, pays-out and takes-up umbilicals, either control hose bundles or armoured electrical cables. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'reference point':{d:'also called gauge point.',l:''},'regulator (pressure)':{d:'a hydraulic device that reduces upstream supply pressure to a desired (regulated) pressure. It may be manual or remotely operated and, once set, will automatically maintain the regulated output pressure unless reset to a different pressure.',l:''},'relative density':{d:'the ration of the mass of a given volume of a substance to the mass of a like volume of a standard substance, such as water or air. In conventional measurement units, specific gravity is similar to relative density.',l:''},'relief valve':{d:'a device that is built into a hydraulic or pneumatic system to relieve (dump) any excess pressure.',l:''},'relief well':{d:'a well drilled near and deflected into a well that is out of control, making it possible to bring the wild well under control. See wild well.',l:''},'remote BOP control panel':{d:'a device, placed on the rig floor, that can be operated by the Driller to direct air pressure to actuating cylinders that turn the control valves on the main BOP control unit, located at a safe distance from the rig.',l:''},'remote choke panel':{d:'a set of controls, usually placed on the rig floor, that is manipulated to control the amount of drilling fluid being circulated out through the choke manifold. This procedure is necessary when a kick is being circulated out of a well. See choke manifold.',l:''},'remote control valve':{d:'a valve which is controlled from a remote location.',l:''},'replacement':{d:'the process whereby a volume of fluid equal to the volume of steel in tubulars and tools withdrawn from the well bore is returned to the well bore. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'reservoir':{d:'a subsurface, porous, permeable rock body in which oil and/or gas is stored. Most reservoir rocks are limestone’s, dolomites, sandstone’s, or a combination of these. The three basic types of hydrocarbon reservoirs are oil, gas and condensate. An oil reservoir generally contains three fluids – gas, oil, and water – with oil the dominant product. In the typical oil reservoir, these fluids occur in different phases because of the variance in their gravity’s. Gas, the lightest, occupies the upper part of the reservoir rocks; water, the lower part; and oil, the intermediate section. In addition to its occurrence as a cap or in solution, gas may accumulate independently of the oil; if so, the reservoir is called a gas reservoir. Associated with the gas, in most instances, are salt water and some oil. In a condensate reservoir, the hydrocarbons may exist as a gas, but, when brought to the surface, some of he heavier ones condense to a liquid.',l:''},'reservoir drive mechanism':{d:'the process in which reservoir fluids are caused to flow out of the reservoir rock and into a well bore by natural energy. Gas drives depend on the fact that, as the reservoir is produced, pressure is reduced, allowing the gas to expand and provide the driving energy. Water-drive reservoirs depend on water pressure to force the hydrocarbons out of the reservoirs and into the well bore.',l:''},'reservoir pressure':{d:'the pressure in a reservoir.',l:''},'reservoir rock':{d:'a permeable rock that contains oil or gas in appreciable quantity.',l:''},'response time':{d:'the time elapsed between activation of a function at the control panel and complete operation of the function. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'retarder':{d:'a substance added to cement to prolong the setting time so that the cement can be pumped into place. Retarder\u0027s are used for cementing in high-temperature formations.',l:''},'retrievable control pod':{d:'a subsea pod that is retrievable remotely on a wire line. (API Recommended Practice 16E).',l:''},'returns':{d:'the fluid, cuttings, and so forth that circulate up the hole to the surface.',l:''},'reverse circulation':{d:'the course of drilling fluid downward through the annulus and upward through the drill stem, in contrast to normal circulation in which the course is downward through the drill stem and upward through the annulus. Seldom used in open hole, but frequently used in workover operations. Also referred to as “circulating the short way”, since returns from bottom can be obtained more quickly than in normal circulation.',l:''},'reverse-circulation junk basket':{d:'a special device that is lowered into the hole during normal circulation to a position over the junk to be retrieved. A ball is then pumped down to cause the drilling fluid to exit through nozzles in the tool, producing reverse circulation and creating a vacuum inside the tool so that the junk is sucked into it.',l:''},'RF ':{d:'Rig Floor',l:''},'rheology':{d:'the study of the flow of gases and liquids, of special importance to fluid engineers and reservoir engineers.',l:''},'rig':{d:'the derrick or mast, draw-works, and attendant surface equipment of a drilling or workover unit.',l:''},'rig floor':{d:'the area immediately around the rotary table and extending to each corner of the derrick or the mast; the area immediately above the substructure on which the draw-works, rotary table, and so forth rest. Also called derrick floor and drill floor.',l:''},'RIH ':{d:'Run In Hole',l:''},'ring-joint flange':{d:'a special type of flanged connection in which a metal ring (resting in a groove in the flange) serves as a pressure seal between the two flanges.',l:''},'riser':{d:'a pipe through which liquid travels upward; a riser pipe. See riser pipe.',l:''},'riser angle indicator':{d:'an acoustic or electronic device used to monitor the angle of the flex joint on a floating offshore drilling rig. Usually, a small angle should be maintained on the flex joint to minimise drill pipe fatigue and wear and damage to the Blowout Preventers and to maximise the ease with which tools may be run. Also called azimuth angle indicator.',l:''},'riser connector (LMRP connector)':{d:'a hydraulically operated connector that joins the Lower Marine Riser Package to the top of the lower BOP stack. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'riser pipe':{d:'the pipe and special fittings used on floating offshore drilling rigs to establish a seal between the top of the well bore, which is on the ocean floor, and the drilling equipment, located above the surface of the water. A riser pipe serves as a guide for the drill stem from the drilling vessel to the well head and as a conductor of drilling fluid from the well to the vessel. The riser consists of several sections of pipe and includes special devices to compensate for any movement of the drilling rig caused by waves. It is also called a marine riser.',l:''},'riser section':{d:'one of the sections in Interval 0 created when a drillship or semi-submersible rig is selcted. The riser section represents the riser pipe, through which liquid travels upward, that connects a floating drilling vessel to the subsea wellhead.',l:''},'riser spider':{d:'equipment used to support the marine riser while it is being run or retrieved. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'riser tensioned line':{d:'a cable that supports the marine riser while compensating for vessel movement.',l:''},'RMS ':{d:'Reservoir Monitoring System',l:''},'rock':{d:'an aggregate of different minerals. Rocks are divided into three groups on the basis of their mode of origin: igneous, metamorphic, and sedimentary.',l:''},'rock bit':{d:'also called roller cone bit. See roller cone bit.',l:''},'roller cone bit':{d:'a drilling bit made of two, three, or four cones, or cutters, that are mounted on extremely rugged bearings. Also called rock bits. The surface of each cone is made up of rows of steel teeth or rows of tungsten carbide inserts.',l:''},'ROP':{d:'rate of penetration',l:''},'ROSS ':{d:'Remote Operated Sliding Sleeve (Weatherford product)',l:''},'ROSS-V ':{d:'Remote Operated Variable Choke',l:''},'rotary':{d:'the machine used to impart rotational power to the drill stem permitting vertical movement of the pipe for rotary drilling. Modern rotary machines have a special component, the rotary bushing, to turn the Kelly bushing, which permits vertical movement of the Kelly while the stem is turning.',l:''},'rotary bushing':{d:'also called master bushing.',l:''},'rotary drilling':{d:'a drilling method in which a hole is drilled by a rotating bit to which a downward force is applied. The bit is fastened to and rotated by the drill stem, which also provides a passageway through which the drilling fluid is circulated. Additional joints of drill pipe are added as drilling progresses.',l:''},'rotary hose':{d:'a reinforced flexible tube on a rotary drilling rig that conducts the drilling fluid from the fluid pump and standpipe to the swivel and Kelly; also called the fluid hose or the Kelly hose.',l:''},'rotary line':{d:'also called drilling line.',l:''},'rotary pump':{d:'a pump that moves fluid by positive displacement, using a system of rotating vanes, gears, or lobes. The vaned pump has vanes extending radially from element mounted in the casing. The geared rotary pump uses opposite rotating, meshing gears or lobes. rotary slips n pl.: also called slips. See slips.',l:''},'rotary support beams':{d:'the steel beams of a substructure which supports the rotary table. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'rotary table':{d:'the principal component of a rotary, or rotary machine, used to turn the drill stem and support the drilling assembly. It has a bevelled gear arrangement to create the rotational movement and an opening into which bushings are fitted to drive and support the drilling assembly.',l:''},'rotating blowout preventer':{d:'also called a rotating head.',l:''},'rotating drilling head':{d:'a sealing device used to close off the annular space around the Kelly in drilling with pressure at the surface, usually installed above the main Blowout Preventers. A rotating head makes it possible to drill ahead even when there is pressure in the annulus that the weight of the drilling fluid is not overcoming; the head prevents the well from blowing out. It is used mainly in drilling of formations that have low permeability. the rate of penetration through such formations is usually rapid.',l:''},'rotating stripper head':{d:'a sealing device installed above the Blowout Preventers and used to close the annular space about the drill pipe or Kelly when pulling or running pipe under pressure. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'round trip':{d:'the action of pulling out and subsequently running back into the hole a string of drill pipe or tubing. making a round trip is also called tripping.',l:''},'ROV ':{d:'Remote Operated Vehicle – as in mini submarine',l:''},'RRP ':{d:'Reciprocating Rod Pumps / Pumping',l:''},'RSS ':{d:'Rotatable Steering System',l:''},'RT ':{d:'Rotary Table',l:''},'RTS ':{d:'Rotary Traction Systems (for Coil Tubing)',l:''},'sack':{d:'a container for cement, bentonite, illuminate, barite, caustic, and so forth. Sacks (bags) contain the following amounts: Cement 94 lb (1 cu ft) Bentonite 100 lb Ilmenite 100 lb Barite 100 lm',l:''},'safety clamp':{d:'a device used to suspend a rod string after the pump has been spaced or when the weight of the rod string must be taken off the pumping equipment.',l:''},'safety joint':{d:'an accessory to fishing tool, placed above it. If the tool cannot be disengaged from the fish, the safety point permits easy disengagement of the string of pipe above the safety joint. Thus, part of the safety joint, as well as the tool attached to the fish remains in the hole and becomes part of the fish.',l:''},'safety valve':{d:'1. an automatic valve that opens or closes when an abnormal condition occurs (e.g., a pressure relief valve on a separator that opens if the pressure exceeds the set point, or the shutdown valve at the well head that closes if the line pressure becomes too high or too low). 2. a valve installed at the top of the drill stem to prevent flow out of the drill pipe if a kick occurs during tripping operations.',l:''},'salt dome':{d:'as dome that is caused by an intrusion of rock salt into overlying sediments. A peircement salt dome is one that has been pushed up so that it penetrates the overlying sediments, leaving them truncated. The formations above the salt plug are usually arched so that they dip in all directions away from the centre of the dome, thus frequently forming traps for petroleum accumulations.',l:''},'salt water flow':{d:'an influx of formation salt water into the well bore. (API Recommended Practice 53).',l:''},'sandstone':{d:'a detrital sedimentary rock composed of individual grains of sand (commonly quartz) that are cemented together by silica, calcium carbonate, iron oxide, and so forth. Sandstone is a common rock in which petroleum and water accumulate.',l:''},'saturation':{d:'a state of being filled or permeated to capacity. sometimes used to mean the degree or percentage of saturation (as, the saturation of the pore space in a formation or the saturation of gas in a liquid, both in reality meaning the extent of saturation).',l:''},'SBP':{d:'surface backpressure',l:''},'scf':{d:'standard cubic feet',l:''},'scf/d':{d:'standard cubic feet per day',l:''},'SCR':{d:'Slow Circulating Rate.',l:''},'scrubber':{d:'a scrubber is a type of separator which has been designed to handle flow streams with unusually high gas-to-liquid ratio. These are commonly used in conjunction with dehydrators, extraction plants, instruments or compressors for protection from entrained. (API Specification 12J)',l:''},'SCSSV ':{d:'Surface Controlled Subsurface Safety Valve (also known as SCSSSV)',l:''},'sea floor':{d:'the bottom of the ocean; the seabed.',l:''},'secondary cementing':{d:'any cementing operation after the primary cementing operation. secondary cementing includes a plug-back job, in which a plug of cement is positioned at a specific point in the well and allowed to set. Wells ate plugged to shut off bottom water or to reduce the depth of the well for the other reasons.',l:''},'secondary control':{d:'the proper use of blowout prevention equipment to control the well in the event primary control is lost.',l:''},'SECT ':{d:'Single Ended Connectorized Transducer',l:''},'sediment':{d:'1. the matter that settles to the bottom of a liquid; also called tank bottoms, basic sediment, and so forth. 2. in geology, buried layers of sedimentary rocks.',l:''},'sedimentary rock':{d:'a rock composed of materials that were transported to their present position by wind or water. Sandstone, shale, and limestone are sedimentary rocks.',l:''},'selector valve':{d:'a three position directional control valve that has the pressure inlet port blocked and the operator ports blocked in the centre position. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'self-elevating drilling unit':{d:'an offshore drilling rig, usually with a large hull. It ahs a mat or legs that ate lowered to the sea floor and a main deck that is raised above the surface of the water to a distance where it will not be affected by the waves. Also called a jack-up drilling rig.',l:''},'semi-submersible drilling rig':{d:'a floating offshore drilling structure that has hulls submerged in the water not resting on the sea floor. Living quarters, storage space, and so forth are assembled on the deck. Semi-submersible rigs are either self-propelled or towed to a drilling site and either anchored or dynamically positioned over the site or both. They are more stable than drill ships and are used extensively to drill wells in deep and rough waters.',l:''},'semisub rig':{d:'a floating offshore drilling rig that has submerged hulls that do not rest on the sea floor. Semi-submersible rigs are typically used to drill wells in deep or rough water.',l:''},'separator':{d:'a separator is a cylindrical or spherical vessel used in the field to remove well-stream liquid(s) from gas components. The separators remove may be either may be either two-phase or three-phase. Two-phase separators also remove the total liquid form the gas, while three-phase separators also remove free water from the hydrocarbon liquid. Corrosion consideration for separators shall be for the pressure containing parts of the vessel only, and as can be identified as falling within the requirements of the applicable sections of the ASME Code. Corrosion considerations for vessel internals (non-pressure parts) is the mutual agreement between the purchaser and the manufacturer. Material selection for corrosive fluids should be selected based on a review of related API or NACE publications for materials that conform to ASME Code. Consideration should be given to material selection as it relates to weight loss, sulphide stress cracking, chloride stress cracking, or other forms of corrosion. It is the responsibility of the user to determine what consideration for corrosion should be made to the vessel during its intended life (Reference ASME Code as applicable to corrosion). (API Specification 12J)',l:''},'serialisation':{d:'assignment of a unique code to individual parts and/or pieces of equipment to maintain records.',l:''},'shale':{d:'a fine-grained sedimentary rock composed of consolidated silt and clay or fluid. Shale is the most frequently occurring sedimentary rock.',l:''},'shale shaker':{d:'a vibrating screen used to remove cuttings from the circulating fluid in rotary drilling operations. The size of the openings in the screen should be carefully selected to be the smallest size possible that will allow 100 per cent flow of the fluid. Also called a shaker.',l:''},'shear ram':{d:'the components in a Blowout Preventer that cut, or shear, through drill pipe and form a seal against well pressure. Shear rams are used in mobile offshore drilling operations to provide a quick method of moving the rig away from the hole when there is no time to trip the drill stem out of the hole.',l:''},'shear ram (BOP) (blind/shear rams)':{d:'rams have cutting blades that will shear tubulars that may be in the well bore, while the rams close and seal against the pressure below. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'shear stress':{d:'arises from a force vector component parallel to the cross section',l:''},'sheave':{d:'a wheel or rollers with a cross-section designed to allow a specific size of rope, cable, wireline or hose bundle to be routed around it at a fixed bend radius. Normally used to change the direction of, and support, the line. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'shooting nipple assembly':{d:'a fabricated length of pipe equipped with a wireline Blowout Preventer and pack-off installed above the Blowout Preventer stack to accommodate removal of logging or perforating tools and for protection against unexpected pressure while performing through-casing wireline operations.',l:''},'shut in':{d:'1. to close the valves on a well so that it stops producing. 2. to close in a well in which a kick has occurred. See Hard Shut In, Soft Shut In.',l:''},'shut-in bottom-hole pressure':{d:'the pressure at the bottom of a well when the surface valves on the well are completely closed. The pressure is caused by fluids that exist in the formation at the bottom of the well.',l:''},'shut-in casing pressure':{d:'pressure of the annular fluid on the casing when a well is shut in.',l:''},'shut-in drill pipe pressure':{d:'pressure of the drilling fluid on the inside of the drill stem; used to measure the difference between hydrostatic pressure and formation pressure when a well is shut in after a kick and the fluid pump is off.',l:''},'shut-in pressure':{d:'the pressure when the well is completely shut in, as noted on a gauge installed on the surface control valves. When drilling is in progress, shut-in pressure should be zero, because the pressure exerted by the drilling fluid should be equal to or greater than the pressure exerted by the formation through which the well bore passes. on a flowing, producing well, however, shut-in pressure should be above zero.',l:''},'shuttle valve':{d:'a valve with two or more supply pressure ports and only one outlet port. When fluid is flowing through one of the supply ports the internal shuttle seals off the other inlet port and allows flow to the outlet port only. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'SI':{d:'The unit system for the International System, which uses metric units.',l:''},'SIBHP':{d:'shut-in bottom-hole pressure; used in drilling reports.',l:''},'SICP':{d:'shut-in casing pressure.',l:''},'SICP (SICHP) ':{d:'Shut-In Casing (Head) Pressure',l:''},'sidetrack':{d:'to drill around drillpipe or casing that has become lodged permanently in the hole, using whipstock, turbo-drill, or other fluid motor',l:''},'sidetrack well':{d:'A secondary wellbore that deviates from the original well',l:''},'SIDPP':{d:'shut-in drill pipe pressure; used in drilling reports.',l:''},'silicon controlled rectifier':{d:'a device that changes alternating current to direct by means of a silicon control gate. Commonly called SCR or Thyristor.',l:''},'single':{d:'joint of drill pipe.',l:''},'single-shot survey':{d:'a directional survey that provides a single record of the drift direction and off-vertical orientation of the hole.',l:''},'sinusoidal critical force':{d:'axial compression load leading to the sinusoidal buckling of a tubular in a particular constrains',l:''},'SIP':{d:'shut-in pressure, used in drilling reports.',l:''},'site elevation':{d:'elevation of the drilling platform about the field\u0027s vertical reference datum',l:''},'SITP (SITHP) ':{d:'Shut-In Tubing (Head) Pressure',l:''},'SIWP (SIWHP) ':{d:'Shut-In Well (Head) Pressure',l:''},'skid the rig':{d:'to move a rig with a standard derrick from the location of a lost or completed hole preparatory to starting a new hole. Skidding the rig allows the move to be accomplished with little or no dismantling of equipment.',l:''},'slick line':{d:'a smooth, single-strand, high-strength, steel wire used in wireline operations. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'slim-hole drilling':{d:'drilling in which the size of the hole is smaller than the conventional hole diameter for a given depth. This decrease in hole size enables the operator to run smaller casing, thereby lessening the cost of completion.',l:''},'slip ram preventer':{d:'a ram Blowout Preventer with pipe slips which, when engaged, prevents movement of the pipe but does not control flow. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'slips':{d:'wedge-shaped pieces of metal with teeth or other gripping elements that are used to prevent pipe from slipping down into the hole or to hold pipe in place. Rotary slips fit around the drill pipe and wedge against the master bushing to support the pipe. Power slips are pneumatically or hydraulically actuated devices that allow the crew to dispense with the manual handling of slips when making a connection. Packers and other downhole equipment are secured in position by slips that engage the pipe by action directed at the surface.',l:''},'sloughing':{d:'(pronounced “sluffing”). Also called caving. See caving.',l:''},'Slow Circulating Rate (SCR)':{d:'a predetermined pump rate which can be used to kill a well which has experienced a kick.',l:''},'slug the pipe':{d:'to pump a quantity of heavy fluid into the drill pipe. Before hoisting drill pipe, it is desirable (if possible) to pump into its top section a quantity of heavy fluid, or a slug, that causes the level of the fluid to remain below the rig floor so that the crew members and the rig floor are not contaminated with the fluid when stands are broken out.',l:''},'slurry':{d:'a plastic mixture of cement and water that is pumped into a well to harden, where it supports the casing into a well to harden, where it supports the casing and provides a seal in the well bore to prevent migration of underground fluids.',l:''},'SM ':{d:'Single Mode (as in fiber optics)',l:''},'snubbing':{d:'pulling or running tubulars under pressure through a resilient element where special equipment is used to apply external force to push the pipe into the well or to control pipe movement out of the well. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'SO2':{d:'sulphur dioxide.',l:''},'soft shut in':{d:'to close in a well by closing a Blowout Preventer with the choke and choke lien valve open, then closing the choke while monitoring the casing pressure gauge for maximum allowable casing pressure. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'SOIP ':{d:'Standard Oil in Place (measurement of oil in the formation)',l:''},'solenoid valve':{d:'an electrically operated valve that controls a hydraulic or pneumatic pilot signal or function.',l:''},'Solution':{d:'a single, homogeneous liquid, solid or gas phase that is a mixture in which the components (liquid, gas, solid, or combinations thereof) are uniformly distributed throughout the mixture. In a solution, the dissolved substance is called the solute, the substance in which the solute is dissolved is called the solvent.',l:''},'sour':{d:'Containing or caused by hydrogen sulphide or another acid gas (e.g., sour crude, sour gas, sour corrosion).',l:''},'sour crude oil':{d:'oil containing hydrogen sulphide or another acid gas.',l:''},'sour gas':{d:'natural gas containing hydrogen sulphide.',l:''},'space out':{d:'procedure conducted to position a predetermined length pipe above the rotary table so that a tool joint is located above the subsea preventer rams on which drill pipe is to be suspended (hung-off) and so that no tool joint is opposite a set of preventer rams after drill pipe is hung-off. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'space-our joint':{d:'the joint of drill pipe which is used in hang off operations so that no tool joint is opposite a set of preventer rams. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'SPE':{d:'Society of Petroleum Engineers',l:''},'specific gravity':{d:'the ratio of the weight of a given volume of a substance at a given temperature to the weight of an equal volume of a standard substance at the same temperature. For example, if 1 cubic inch of water at 39ºF weighs 1 unit and 1 cubic inch of another solid or liquid at 39º weights 0.95 unit, then the specific gravity of the substance is 0.95. In determining the specific gravity of gases, the comparison is made with the standard of air or hydrogen.',l:''},'spent fluid':{d:'hydraulic fluid that is vented from a function control port when the opposite function is operated.',l:''},'Spf (spm) ':{d:'Shots per foot (shots per meter) – density of perforating holes',l:''},'splash zone':{d:'the area on an offshore structure that is regularly wetted by seawater but is not continuously submerged. Metal in the splash zone must be well protected from the corrosive action of seawater and air.',l:''},'SPM ':{d:'Side Pocket Mandrel',l:''},'spool':{d:'a pressure containing piece of equipment having API end connections, used below or between equipment functioning to space apart, adapt or provide outlets in an equipment assembly. When outlet connections are provided, they shall be API connections.',l:''},'SPP':{d:'standpipe pressure',l:''},'spud':{d:'to move the drill stem up and down in the hole over a short distance without rotation. Careless execution of this operation creates pressure surges that can cause a formation to break down and results in lost circulation. See spud in.',l:''},'spud in':{d:'to begin drilling, to start the hole.',l:''},'SPV ':{d:'Self Piloting Injection Valve',l:''},'square drill collar':{d:'a special drill collar, square but with rounded edges, used to control the straightness or direction of the hole, often part of a packed-hole assembly.',l:''},'square-drive master bushing':{d:'a master bushing that has a square opening or recess to accept and drive the square that is on the bottom of the square-drive Kelly bushing.',l:''},'squeeze':{d:'1. a cementing operation in which cement is pumped behind the casing under high pressure to re-cement channelled areas or to block off an un-cemented zone. 2. the increasing of external pressure upon a diver’s body by improper diving technique.',l:''},'squeeze cementing':{d:'the forcing of cement slurry by pressure to specified points in a well to cause seals at the points of squeeze. It is a secondary cementing method that is used to isolate a producing formation, seal off water, repair casing leaks, and so forth.',l:''},'squench joint':{d:'a special thread-less tool joint for large-diameter pipe, especially conductor pipe, sometimes used on offshore drilling rigs. When the box is brought down over the pin and weight is applied, a locking device is required to make up these joints, their use can save time when the conductor pipe is being run.',l:''},'SRO ':{d:'Surface Readout',l:''},'SRT ':{d:'Sucker Rod Thread',l:''},'SS ':{d:'Stainless Steel',l:''},'SSC ':{d:'Sulphide Stress Cracking – corrosion related',l:''},'SSD ':{d:'Sliding Side Door',l:''},'SSSV ':{d:'Subsurface Safety Valve',l:''},'SSV ':{d:'Surface Safety Valve',l:''},'stab':{d:'to guide the end pipe into coupling or tool joint when making up a connection.',l:''},'stabbing board':{d:'a temporary platform erected in the derrick or mast, some 20 to 40 feet (6-12m) above the derrick floor, The Derrickman or another crew member works on the board while casing is being run in a well. The board may be wooden or fabricated of steel girders floored with anti-skid material and powered electrically to be raised or lowered to the desired level. A stabbing board serves the same purpose as a monkey board but is temporary instead of permanent.',l:''},'stabiliser':{d:'1. a tool placed near the bit, and often just above it, in the drilling assembly and used to change the deviation angle in a well by controlling the location of the contact point between the hole and the drill collars. Conversely, stabilisers are used to maintain correct hole angle. See packed hole assembly. 2. a vessel in which hydrocarbon vapours are separated from liquids. 3. a fractionation system that reduces the vapour pressure so that the resulting liquid is less volatile.',l:''},'stabilizer':{d:'A component placed in the BHA to control the deviation of the wellbore. One or more stabilizers may be used to achieve the intended well path.',l:''},'stack':{d:'1. a vertical pile of blowout prevention equipment. Also called preventer stack. See Blowout Preventer. 2. The vertical chimney-like installation that is the waste disposal system for unwanted vapour such as flue gases or tail-gas streams.',l:''},'stack a rig':{d:'to store a drilling rig upon completion of a job when the rig is to be drawn from operation for a time.',l:''},'stand':{d:'the connected joints of pipe racked in the derrick or mast during a trip. The usual stand is 90 feet long (about 27m), which is three lengths of drill pipe screwed together (a treble).',l:''},'standard cubic foot':{d:'a gas volume unit of measurement at a specific temperature and pressure. The temperature and pressure may be defined in the gas sales contract or by reference to other standard. Its abbreviation is scf.',l:''},'standard pressure':{d:'the pressure exerted by a column of mercury 760 mm high; equivalent to 14.7 psia.',l:''},'standard temperature':{d:'a predetermined temperature used as a basic measurement. The petroleum industry uses 60ºF (15.5ºC) as its standard temperature during measurement of oil. The volume of a quantity of oil at its actual temperature (assuming it is not 60ºF) is converted to the volume the oil would occupy at 60ºF. Conversion is aided by the use of API conversion tables.',l:''},'standard well kill procedure':{d:'any of industry’s proven techniques to control a flowing well wherein well control is obtained through pumping drilling fluid of increased density at a predetermined pumping rate with Blowout Preventer(s) closed and simultaneously controlling casing and drill pipe surface pressures by varying choke manifold choke settings until the well is stable and static with zero surface pressure. (API Recommended Practice 64).',l:''},'standpipe':{d:'a vertical pipe rising along the side of the derrick or mast, which joins the discharge line leading from the fluid pump to the rotary hose and through which fluid is pumped going into the hole.',l:''},'starboard':{d:'(nautical) the right side of a vessel (determined by looking toward the bow).',l:''},'STD ':{d:'Standard',l:''},'steel-tooth bit':{d:'a roller cone bit which the surface of each cone is made up of rows of steel teeth. Also called a milled-tooth bit or milled bit.',l:''},'still drilling assembly':{d:'also called packed-hole assembly. See packed-hole assembly.',l:''},'stored hydraulic fluid volume':{d:'the fluid volume recoverable from the accumulator system between the maximum designed accumulator operating pressure and the precharge pressure. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'straight hole':{d:'a hole that is drilled vertically. the total hole angle is restricted, and the hole does not change direction rapidly – no more than 3º per 100 feet (30.48 m) of hole.',l:''},'straight-through function':{d:'a subsea function that is directly operated by a pilot signal without interface with a pod mounted pilot operated control valve. Straight-through functions typically require a low fluid volume to operate and the response time is not critical. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'stress relief':{d:'controlled heating of material to a predetermined temperature for the purpose of reducing any residual stresses after welding. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'strip a well':{d:'to pull rods and tubing from a well at the same time – for example, when the pump is stuck. Tubing must be stripped over the rods a joint at a time, and the exposed sucker rod is then backed off and removed.',l:''},'strip pipe':{d:'1. to remove the drill stem from the hole while the Blowout Preventers are closed. 2. to pull the drill stem and the wash over pipe out of the hole at the same time.',l:''},'stripper head':{d:'a blowout prevention device consisting of a gland and packing arrangement bolted to the well head. It is often used to seal the annular space between the tubing and casing.',l:''},'stripping in':{d:'1. the process of lowering the drill stem into the well bore when the well is shut in on a kick. 2. the process of putting tubing into a well under pressure.',l:''},'structural casing':{d:'the outer string of large diameter, heavy-wall pipe installed in wells drilled from floating installation to resist the bending movements imposed by the marine riser, and to help support the well-head installed on the conductor casing. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'stuck pipe':{d:'drill pipe, drill collars, casing, or tubing having inadvertently become immovable in the hole. Sticking may occur when drilling is in progress, when casing is being run in the hole, or when the drill pipe is being hoisted.',l:''},'stuck point':{d:'the depth in the hole at which the drill stem, tubing, or casing is stuck.',l:''},'studded connections':{d:'connections in which thread-anchored studs are screwed into tapped holes. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'stuffing box':{d:'a packing gland screwed in the top of the well head through which the polished rod operates on a pumping well. It prevents the escape of oil, diverting it into a side outlet to which is connected the flow line, leading to the oil and gas separator or the field storage tank.',l:''},'submersible rig':{d:'a floating offshore rig that is fully flooded at the drill site so that it rests on the sea floor. Submersibles are typically used in relatively shallow water.',l:''},'subsea blowout preventer':{d:'a Blowout Preventer placed on the sea floor for use by a floating offshore drilling rig.',l:''},'subsea test tree':{d:'a device designed to be landed in a subsea well head or Blowout Preventer stack to provide a means of closing in the well on the ocean floor so that a drill stem test of an offshore well can be obtained.',l:''},'subsurface safety valve':{d:'a device installed in the production tubing in a well below the well head and designed to prevent uncontrolled well flow when actuated. These devices can be installed and retrieved by wireline (wireline retrievable) and pump down methods, or be an integral part of the tubing string (tubing retrievable). (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'suction pit':{d:'also called a suction tank, sump pit, or fluid suction pit. suction tank',l:''},'suction tank':{d:'the fluid tank from which fluid is picked up by the suction of the fluid pumps. sulphate-reducing bacteria',l:''},'sulphate-reducing bacteria':{d:'bacteria that digest sulphate present in water, causing the release of hydrogen sulphide, which combines with iron to form iron sulphide, a troublesome scale.',l:''},'supercharge':{d:'to supply a charge of air to the intake of an internal-combustion engine at a pressure higher than that of the surrounding atmosphere.',l:''},'surface casing':{d:'also called surface pipe.',l:''},'surface pressure':{d:'pressure measure at the well head.',l:''},'surface safety valve':{d:'a Christmas tree valve and actuator assembly designed to prevent uncontrolled well flow when actuated. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'surface torque':{d:'torque applied at the well surface to overcome integral string turning motion resistance',l:''},'surface-motion compensator':{d:'a heave compensator.',l:''},'surge':{d:'1. an accumulation of liquid above a normal or average level, or a sudden increase in its flow rate above a normal flow rate. 2. the motion of a mobile offshore drilling rig in a direction in line with the centre line of the rig, especially the front-to-back motion of the rig when it is moored in a sea-way.',l:''},'surge effect':{d:'a rapid increase in pressure down hole that occurs when the drill stem is lowered rapidly or when the fluid pump is quickly brought up to speed after speeding.',l:''},'surge EMW vs. bit depth':{d:'a record showing the calculated surge pressure plus mud weight (EMW) for a given run rate compared to bit depth',l:''},'surging':{d:'a rapid increase in pressure down hole that occurs when the drill stem is lowered too fast or when the fluid pump is brought up to speed after starting.',l:''},'swab':{d:'n: a hollow, rubber-faced cylinder mounted on a hollow mandrel with a pin joint on the upper end to connect to the swab line. A check valve that opens upward on the lower end provides a way to remove the fluid from the well when pressure is insufficient to support flow; v: to operate a swab on a wireline to bring well fluids to the surface when the well does not flow naturally. Swabbing is temporary operation to determine whether or not the well can be made to flow. If the well does not flow after being swabbed, pump is installed as a permanent lifting device to bring the oil to the surface.',l:''},'swab EMW vs. bit depth':{d:'a record showing the calculated swab pressure plus mud weight (EMW) for a user-set minimum EMW compared to bit depth',l:''},'swab valve':{d:'the uppermost valve in vertical line on the Christmas tree, always above the flow-wing valve. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'swabbed show':{d:'formation fluid that is pulled into the well bore because of an underbalance of formation pressure caused by pulling the drill string too fast.',l:''},'swabbing effect':{d:'phenomenon characterised by formation fluids being pulled or swabbed into the well bore when the drill stem and bit are pulled up the well bore fast enough to reduce the hydrostatic pressure of the fluid below the bit. If enough formation fluid is swabbed into the hole, a kick can result.',l:''},'sweet crude oil':{d:'oil containing little or no sulphur, especially little or no hydrogen sulphide.',l:''},'sweet gas':{d:'gas that has no more than the maximum sulphur content defined by (1) the specifications for the sales gas from a plant or (2) the definition by a legal body such as the Railroad Commission of Texas.',l:''},'switchable three-way target valve':{d:'a device having an erosion resistant target with changeable position to enable selection of flow direction of diverted well fluids. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'swivel':{d:'a rotary tool that is hung from the rotary hook and travelling block to suspend and permit free rotation of the drill stem. It also provides a connection for the rotary hose and a passageway for the flow of drilling fluid into the drill stem.',l:''},'swivel packing':{d:'special rubberised compounds placed in a swivel to prevent drilling fluid from leaking out under high pressure.',l:''},'t':{d:'tonne',l:''},'T-FOCA II ':{d:'Tactical Fiber Optic Connector Assembly',l:''},'tail pipe':{d:'1. a pipe run in a well below a packer. 2. pipe used to exhaust gases from the muffler of an engine to the outside atmosphere.',l:''},'take out':{d:'to remove a joint or stand of pipe, casing, or tubing that is to be run in a well.',l:''},'tapered string':{d:'drill pipe, tubing, sucker rods, and so forth with a diameter near the top of the well larger than the diameter below.',l:''},'tar sand':{d:'a sandstone that chiefly contains very heavy, tar like hydrocarbons. Tar sands are difficult to produce by ordinary methods; thus it is costly to obtain usable hydrocarbon from them.',l:''},'target':{d:'a bull plug or blind flange at the end of a tee to prevent erosion at a point where change in flow direction occurs. (API Recommended Practice 53)',l:''},'targeted':{d:'refers to a fluid piping system in which flow impinges upon a lead-filled end (target) or a piping tee when fluid transits a change in direction. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'TBF ':{d:'Top (of) Bottom Flange',l:''},'TBG (tbg) ':{d:'Tubing (tbg)',l:''},'TCP ':{d:'Tubing Conveyed Perforator',l:''},'TD ':{d:'Total Depth',l:''},'TDH ':{d:'Total Dynamic Head (ESP related)',l:''},'TDR ':{d:'Time Domain Reflector',l:''},'TEC ':{d:'Tubing Encapsulated Conductor',l:''},'telescopic (slip) joint packer':{d:'a torus-shaped hydraulic or pneumatically actuated, resilient element between the inner and outer barrels of the telescopic (slip) joint which serves to retain drilling fluid inside the marine riser.',l:''},'telescoping joint':{d:'a device used in the marine riser system of a mobile offshore drilling rig to compensate for the vertical motion of the rig caused by wind, waves, or weather. It consists of an inner barrel attached beneath the rig floor and an outer barrel attached to the riser pipe and is an integrated part of the riser system.',l:''},'telltale hole':{d:'a hole drilled into the space between ring of packing material used with a liner in a fluid pump. When the liner packing fails, fluid spurts out of the telltale hole with each stroke of the piston, indicating that the packing must be renewed.',l:''},'temporary guide base':{d:'the initial piece of equipment lowered to the ocean floor once a mobile offshore drilling rig has been positioned on location. It serves as an anchor for the guidelines and as a foundation for the permanent guide base and has an opening in the centre through which the bit passes. It is also called a template.',l:''},'tensile strength':{d:'the greatest longitudinal stress that a metal can bear with out tearing apart. Tensile strength of a metal is greater than yield strength.',l:''},'tensioner system':{d:'a system of devices installed on a floating offshore drilling rig to maintain a constant tension on the riser pipe despite any vertical motion made by the rig. The guidelines must also be tensioned, and a separate tensioner system is provided for them.',l:''},'Texas deck':{d:'the main load-bearing deck of an offshore drilling structure and the highest above the water, excluding auxiliary decks such as the helicopter landing pad.',l:''},'TFA':{d:'total fluid area',l:''},'TH ':{d:'Tubing Hanger',l:''},'thermal gradient':{d:'the rate that the formation temperature changes across a specified distance',l:''},'thermometer':{d:'an instrument that measures temperature. Thermometers provide a way to estimate temperature from its effect on a substance with known characteristics (such as a gas that expands when heated). Various types of thermometers measure temperature by measuring the change in pressure of a gas kept at a constant volume, the change in electrical resistance of metals, or the galvanic effect of dissimilar metals in contact. The most common thermometer is the mercury-filled glass tube that indicates temperature by the expansion of the liquid mercury.',l:''},'thermostat':{d:'a control device used to regulate temperature.',l:''},'THF ':{d:'Tubing Hanger Flange',l:''},'thief formation':{d:'a formation that absorbs drilling fluid as the fluid is circulated in the well; also called a thief sand or a thief zone. Lost circulation is cause by a thief formation.',l:''},'thixotropic':{d:'the property exhibited by a fluid that is in a liquid state when flowing and in a semisolid, gelled state when at rest. Most drilling fluids must be thixotropic so that the cuttings in the fluid will remain in suspension when circulation is stopped.',l:''},'THP ':{d:'Tubing Head Pressure',l:''},'THS ':{d:'Tubing Hanger Spool',l:''},'tie-back string':{d:'casing that is run from the top of a liner to the surface. A tie-back string is often used to provide a production casing that has not been drilled through.',l:''},'tight formation':{d:'a petroleum or water-bearing formation of relatively low porosity and permeability.',l:''},'tight hole':{d:'1. a well about which information is restricted for security or competitive reasons and such information given only to those authorised to receive it. 2. a section of the hole that, for some reason, is under-gauge. For example, a bit that is worn under-gauge will drill a tight hole.',l:''},'tight spot':{d:'a section of a borehole in which excessive wall cake has built up, reducing the hole diameter and making it difficult to run the tools in and out. Compare key seat.',l:''},'TJ ':{d:'Travel Joint',l:''},'TLP ':{d:'Tension Leg Platform',l:''},'TLV ':{d:'Threshold Limit Valve',l:''},'TNP':{d:'thermal neutron porosity',l:''},'ton':{d:'1. (nautical) a volume measure equal to 100 ft³ applied to mobile offshore drilling rigs. 2. (metric) a measure of weight equal to 1000 kg. Usually spelled tonne.',l:''},'tonne':{d:'a mass unit in the metric system equal to 1000 kg.',l:''},'tool geometry':{d:'A drillstring tool\u0027s outside and inside diameters. Several changes in these measurements may occur along the length of a tool, making discretization necessary.',l:''},'tool joint':{d:'a heavy coupling element for drill pipe, made of special alloy steel. Tool joints have coarse, tapered threads and seating shoulders designed to sustain the weight of the drill stem, withstand strain of frequent coupling and uncoupling, and provide a leak-proof seal. the male section of the joint, or the pin, is attached to one end of the drill pipe, and the female section, or the box, is attached to the other end. The tool joint may be welded to the end of the pipe, screwed on, or both. a hard-metal facing is often applied in a bas around the outside of the tool joint to enable it to resist abrasion from the wall of the borehole.',l:''},'torque':{d:'1. the product of a force applied through a lever arm to product a rotating or turning motion\n\n2. the turning force that is applied to a shaft or other rotary mechanism to cause it to rotate or tend to do so. Torque is measure in units of length and force (foot-pounds, Newton-metres).',l:''},'torque indicator':{d:'an instrument that measures the amount of torque (turning or twisting action) applied to the drill or casing string. The amount of torque applied to the string is important when joints are being made up.',l:''},'torque recorder':{d:'an instrument that measures and makes a record of the amount of torque (turning or twisting action) applied to the drill or casing string.',l:''},'tortuosity':{d:'unwanted deviation from the planned well trajectory',l:''},'total depth':{d:'the maximum depth reached in a well.',l:''},'tour':{d:'(pronounced “tower”) a working shift for drilling crew or other oil field workers. The most common tour is 8 hours long; the three daily tours are called daylight, evening, and graveyard (or morning). Sometimes 12-hour tours are used, especially on offshore rigs; they are called simply day tour or night tour.',l:''},'toxic substance':{d:'a substance or material which can be detrimental to human health or the functional capacity of a person having exposure to it. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'TP (tp) ':{d:'Test Pressure (usually 1.5x working pressure)',l:''},'transducer':{d:'a device actuated by power from one system and supplying power to another system, usually in a different form. For example, a telephone receiver receives electric power and supplies acoustic power.',l:''},'tricone bit':{d:'a type of bit in which three cone shaped cutting devices are mounted in such a way that they intermesh and rotate together as the bit drills. The bit body may be fitted with nozzles, or jets, through which the frilling fluid is discharged. A one-eye bit is used in soft formations to drill a deviated hole.',l:''},'trip':{d:'n: the operation of hoisting the drill stem out and returning it to the well bore; v: shortened form of “make a trip”. See make a trip.',l:''},'trip gas':{d:'an accumulation of gas which enters the hole while a trip is made. (API Recommended Practice 53)',l:''},'trip margin':{d:'an incremental increase in drilling fluid density to provide an increment of overbalance in order to compensate for effects of swabbing. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'trip tank':{d:'a small fluid tank with a capacity of 10 to 15 bbl, usually with 1-bbl divisions, used exclusively to ascertain the amount of fluid necessary to keep the well bore full with the exact amount of fluid equal to that which the drill pope occupied while in the hole must be pumped into the hole, the drill pipe displaces a certain amount of fluid, and a trip tank again can be used to keep track of this volume.',l:''},'tripping':{d:'the operation of hoisting the drill stem out of and returning it to the well bore; making a trip. See trip.',l:''},'TRS ':{d:'Tubular Running Services',l:''},'TRSSV ':{d:'Tubing Retrievable Subsurface Safety Valve',l:''},'true vertical depth':{d:'the depth of a well measure from the surface straight down to the bottom of the well. The true vertical depth of a well may be quite different from its actual measured depth, because wells are very seldom drilled exactly vertical.',l:''},'TSR ':{d:'Tubing Seal Receptacle',l:''},'TTP ':{d:'Thru Tubing Perforating',l:''},'tubing':{d:'small-diameter pipe that is run into a well to serve as a conduit for the passage of oil and gas to the surface.',l:''},'tubing-less completion':{d:'a method of completing a well in which a small diameter production is set through the producing zone with no tubing or inner production string employed to bring formation fluids to the surface. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'tubular goods (tubular)':{d:'any kind of pipe; also called tubulars. Oil field tubular goods include tubing, casing, drill pipe, and line pipe.',l:''},'tungsten carbide bit':{d:'a type of roller cone bit with inserts made of tungsten carbide. Also called tungsten carbide insert bit',l:''},'tungsten carbide insert bit':{d:'also called tungsten carbide bit. See tungsten carbide bit.',l:''},'turbine motor':{d:'usually called a turbodrill. see turbodrill.',l:''},'turbodrill':{d:'a drilling tool that rotates a bit that is attached to it by the action of drilling fluid on the turbine blades built into the tool. When a turbodrill is used, rotary motion is imparted only at the bit; therefore, it is unnecessary to rotate the drill stem. Although straight holes can be drilled with the tool, it is used most often in directional drilling.',l:''},'turbulent flow':{d:'the flow of a fluid in an erratic, non-linear motion, caused by velocity.',l:''},'TVD':{d:'true vertical depth',l:''},'TWCV ':{d:'Two Way Check Valve',l:''},'twist off':{d:'to part or split drill pipe or drill collars, primarily because of metal fatigue in the pipe or because of mishandling.',l:''},'twist-off':{d:'a complete break in pipe caused by rotational force wrenching damaged pipe apart.',l:''},'U-tube':{d:'a U-shaped tube.',l:''},'U-tubing':{d:'the action of fluids flowing in a U-tube (as heavy fluid forcing lighter down the drill stem and up the annuls).',l:''},'UBD (UB) ':{d:'Underbalanced Drilling',l:''},'UBS ':{d:'Underbalanced Systems',l:''},'UDS \u0026 T ':{d:'Underbalanced Systems and Testing',l:''},'ullage':{d:'the amount by which a tank or a vessel comes short of being full, especially on ships. Ullage in a tank is necessary to allow space for the expansion of the oil in the tank when the temperature increases. Also called outage',l:''},'UMB ':{d:'Universal Motor Base (ESP related)',l:''},'umbilical':{d:'a line that supplies a diver or a diving bell with a lifeline, a breathing gas, communications, a pneumo-fathometer, and if needed, a heat supply.',l:''},'UNA ':{d:'Use No Abbreviations – if there is going to be any doubt!',l:''},'unconfined compressive strength':{d:'the unconstrained rock strength of the formation',l:''},'unconsolidated sandstone':{d:'a sand formation in which individual grains do not adhere to one another. If an unconsolidated sandstone produces oil or gas, it will produce sand as sell, if not controlled or corrected.',l:''},'under-balance':{d:'the amount by which formation presser exceeds pressure exerted by the hydrostatic head of fluid in the well bore. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'underground blowout':{d:'an uncontrolled flow of gas, salt water, or other fluid out of the well bore and into another formation that the well bore has penetrated.',l:''},'unit set':{d:'Definition goes here',l:''},'upper Kelly cock':{d:'the Kelly cock, as distinguished from the drill stem safety valve, sometimes called the lower Kelly cock. See Kelly cock.',l:''},'upset':{d:'to forge the ends of tubular products so that the pipe wall acquires extra thickness and strength near the end. Usually upsetting is performed to provide the thickness needed to form threads so that the tubular goods can be connected; the thickened areas formed by upsetting of tubular goods.',l:''},'upstream':{d:'adv.: in the direction opposite the flow in a line. n: the point in a line or system situated opposite the direction of flow.',l:''},'usable hydraulic fluid':{d:'the hydraulic fluid volume recoverable from the accumulator system between the maximum designed accumulator operating pressure and the minimum operating pressure. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'UTS ':{d:'Ultimate Tensile Strength - Stress',l:''},'V-door':{d:'an opening at floor level in a side of a derrick or mast. The v-door is opposite the draw-works and is used as an entry to bring in drill pipe, casing, and other tools from the pipe rack. The name comes from the fact that on the old standard derrick, the shape of the opening was an inverted V.',l:''},'vacuum':{d:'1. theoretically, a space that is devoid of all matter and that exerts zero pressure. 2. a condition that exists in a system when pressure is reduced below atmospheric pressure.',l:''},'vacuum degasser':{d:'a device in which gas-cut fluid is degassed by the action of a vacuum inside a tank. The gas-cut fluid is pulled into the tank, the gas removed, and the gas-free fluid discharged back into the fluid tank.',l:''},'VAM ':{d:'Vallourec Alexandre Madre - Premium thread',l:''},'vapour':{d:'a substance in the gaseous state, capable of being liquefied by compression or cooling.',l:''},'vent':{d:'an opening in a vessel, line, or pump to permit the escape of air or gas.',l:''},'vent line':{d:'the conduit which directs the flow of diverted well bore fluids away from the drill floor to the atmosphere. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'vent line valve':{d:'a full-opening valve which facilitates the shut off of flow or allows passage of diverted well bore fluids through the vent line. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'vent outlet':{d:'the point at which fluids exit the well bore below the annular sealing device via the vent line. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'venturi effect':{d:'the drop in pressure resulting from the increased velocity of a fluid as it flows through a constricted section of a pipe.',l:''},'vertical':{d:'n: an imaginary line at right angles to the plane of the horizon; adj: of a well bore, straight, not deviated.',l:''},'vertical section':{d:'horizontal distance from the vertical plane',l:''},'viscosity':{d:'a measure of the resistance of a liquid to flow. Resistance is brought about by the internal friction resulting from the combined effects of cohesion and adhesion. The viscosity of petroleum products is commonly expressed in terms of the time required for a specific volume of the liquid to flow through an orifice of a specific size.',l:''},'visual examination':{d:'examination of parts and equipment for visible defects in material and workmanship. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'voids':{d:'cavities in a rock that do not contain solid material but may contain fluid.',l:''},'volumetric efficiency':{d:'actual volume of fluid put out by a pump, divided by the volume displaced by a piston or pistons (or other device) in the pump. Volumetric efficiency is usually expressed as a percentage. For example, if the pump pistons displace 300 cubic inches, but the pump puts only 291 cubic inches per stroke, then the volumetric efficiency of the pump is 97 percent.',l:''},'volumetric non-destructive examination':{d:'examination for internal material defects by radiography acoustic emission or ultrasonic testing. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'von Mises stress':{d:'an equivalent stress that is used to predict yielding of materials under multiaxial loading conditions using results from simple uniaxial tensile tests',l:''},'wait-and-weight method':{d:'a well-killing method in which the well is shut in and the fluid weight is raised the amount required to kill the well. The heavy fluid is then circulated into the well, while at the same time the kick fluids are circulated out. So called because one shuts the well in and waits for the fluid to be weighted before circulation begins.',l:''},'wall cake':{d:'also called filter cake or fluid cake. See fluid cake.',l:''},'wall sticking':{d:'also called differential-pressure sticking. See differential-pressure.',l:''},'washout':{d:'1. excessive well bore enlargement caused by solvent and erosive action of the drilling fluid. 2. a fluid-cut opening caused by fluid leakage.',l:''},'water-base fluid':{d:'a drilling fluid in which the continuous phase is water. In water-base fluids, any additives are dispersed in the water. Compare oil-base fluid.',l:''},'water-base hydraulic fluid':{d:'control fluid mixture composed of water soluble lubricant and water. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'WBD ':{d:'Well Bore Dynamics – WFT course dealing with tubing stresses and tube movement program',l:''},'WCS ':{d:'Well Completions Systems (combined with ALS April 2003 to form CPS)',l:''},'weak zone MD surge risk vs. bit depth':{d:'a record showing EMW versus run in rate at the zone of interest\u0027s middle depth',l:''},'weight cut':{d:'the amount by which drilling fluid density is reduced by entrained formation fluids or air. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'weight indicator':{d:'an instrument near the driller’s position on a drilling rig. It shows both the weight of the drill stem that is hanging from the hook (hook load) and the weight that is placed on the bit by the drill collars (weight on bit).',l:''},'weight on bit':{d:'the difference between the net weight of the entire drill stem and the reduced weight resulting when the bit is resting on bottom.',l:''},'weight up':{d:'to increase the weight or density of drilling fluid by adding weighting material.',l:''},'weighting material':{d:'a material that has a high specific gravity and is used to increase the density of drilling fluids or cement slurries.',l:''},'weld groove':{d:'an area between two metals to be joined that has been prepared to receive weld filler metal. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'weld joint':{d:'a description of the way components are fitted together in order to facilitate joining by welding. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'weld, fabrication':{d:'a weld joining two or more parts. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'weld, non pressure containing':{d:'a weld, the absence of which will not reduce the pressure-containing integrity of the component. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'weld, pressure containing':{d:'a weld, the absence of which will reduce the pressure-containing integrity of the component. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'welding':{d:'the fusion of metals with or without the addition of filler materials. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'well':{d:'the hole made by the drilling bit, which can be open, cased, or both. Also called well bore, borehole, or hole.',l:''},'well bore':{d:'a borehole, the hole drilled by the bit. A well bore may have casing in it or it may be open (uncased); or a portion of it may be cased, and a portion of it may be open. Also called a borehole or hole.',l:''},'well control':{d:'the methods used to prevent a well from blowing out. Such techniques include, but are not limited to, keeping the borehole completely filled with drilling fluid of the proper weight or density during all operations, exercising reasonable care when tripping pipe out of the hole to prevent swabbing, and keeping careful track of the amount of fluid put into the hole to replace the volume of pipe removed from the hole during a trip.',l:''},'wellbore':{d:'the hole drilled by the bit',l:''},'WellCAP':{d:'an accredited “well control” training programme developed by the International Association of Drilling Contractors to ensure a minimum standard of training of personnel employed by member companies.',l:''},'wellhead':{d:'n: the equipment installed at the surface of the well bore. A well head includes such equipment as the casing head and tubing head; adj: pertaining to the well head (e.g. well head pressure).',l:''},'wellhead connector (stack connector)':{d:'a hydraulically operated connector that joins the BOP stack to the subsea well head. (API Recommended Practice 16E)',l:''},'WFT ':{d:'Short for Weatherford (Stock market symbol)',l:''},'WHO ':{d:'Wellhead Outlet',l:''},'wild well':{d:'a well that has blown out of control and from which oil, water, or gas is escaping with great force to the surface; also called a gusher.',l:''},'wildcat well':{d:'a well drilled in an area where no oil or gas production exists',l:''},'wireline operations':{d:'operations performed in a well bore by use of tools which are run and pulled on small diameter slick, braided or electric wireline. (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''},'wireline preventer':{d:'preventers installed on top of the well or drill string as a precautionary measure while running wireline. The preventer packing will close around the wireline. (API Recommended Practice 53)',l:''},'wireline preventers':{d:'preventers installed on top of the well or drill string as a precautionary measure wile running wireline. The preventer packing will close around the wireline. (API Recommended Practice 59)',l:''},'wireline well logging':{d:'the recording of subsurface characteristics by wireline tools. Wireline well logs include acoustic logs, calliper logs, radioactivity logs and resistivity logs.',l:''},'WIS ':{d:'Weatherford Intervention Services (formerly Well Installations Services – now TRS)',l:''},'WOC (woc) ':{d:'Waiting On Cement - To set after cementing operations',l:''},'WOR':{d:'water-oil ratio',l:''},'working pressure':{d:'the maximum pressure at which an item is to be sued as a specified temperature.',l:''},'working pressure rating':{d:'the maximum pressure at which an item is designed for safe operation. (API Recommended Practice 64)',l:''},'WOW (wow) ':{d:'Waiting On Weather - To clear and / or become less rough',l:''},'WP (wp) ':{d:'Working Pressure',l:''},'WRP ':{d:'Wireline Retrievable Plug',l:''},'WTTC ':{d:'Weatherford Technology and Training Center (Spencer Rd)',l:''},'WWS ':{d:'Wire Wrapped (Conventional) Screens',l:''},'XO ':{d:'Cross Over',l:''},'yield point':{d:'the maximum stress that a solid can withstand without undergoing permanent deformation either by plastic flow or by rupture. See tensile strength.',l:''},'yield strength':{d:'the stress level measure at room temperature, expressed in pounds per square inch of loaded area, at which material plastically deforms and will not return to its original dimensions when the load is released. All yield strengths specified in this standard shall be considered as being 0.2% yield offset strength per ASTM A370. (API Specification 16A)',l:''},'YP':{d:'yield point',l:''},'zone':{d:'a term used to distinguish different rock strata (e.g. shale zone, sand zone, pay zone, etc). (API Recommended Practice 57)',l:''}});